{"title_page": "Shin Jung-hyeon", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Shin Jung-hyeon\n| image = \n| caption = \n| background = solo_singer\n| alias = Jackie (Jacky/ Hicky) Shin\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1938|1|4|mf=y}},\n| birth_place = [[Seoul]], [[Korea]]\n| instrument = Vocals, guitar\n| genre = [[Psychedelic rock]], [[folk rock]], pop, [[Soul music|soul]]\n| occupation = Songwriter, singer, guitarist\n| years_active = 1957\u2013present\n| label = Jigu Records\n| associated_acts = Add4, Pearl Sisters, Kim Chu-ja, Shin Joong Hyun & The Men, [[Shin Jung Hyun & Yup Juns|Shin Joong Hyun & Yup Juns]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604\n|hanja=\u7533\u91cd\u9249\n|rr=Sin Junghyeon\n|mr=Sin Chunghy\u014fn\n}}\n{{korean name|[[Shin (Korean name)|Shin]]}}\n'''Shin Jung-hyeon''' Or '''Shin Joong-hyun''' Or '''Sin Junghyeon'''; ({{korean|hangul=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604|hanja=\u7533\u91cd\u9249}}, {{IPA-ko|\u0255ind\u0361\u0291u\u014b\u00e7\u028cn|pron}} or {{IPA-ko|\u0255in|}} {{IPA-ko|t\u0361\u0255u\u014b\u00e7\u028cn|}}; born January 4, 1938)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://100.daum.net/encyclopedia/view/b13s3026n8|title=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604|website=Daum Encyclopedia|language=ko|trans-title=Shin Jung-hyeon|access-date=September 5, 2018}}</ref> is a South Korean rock guitarist and singer-songwriter often referred to as Korea's \"Godfather of Rock.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mnet.com/artist/796/profile|title=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604|website=Mnet|language=ko|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/04/world/asia/04shin.html|title=Korea's Godfather of Rock Makes a Comeback|last=Onishi|first=Norimitsu|date=November 4, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A pioneer of [[Korean rock]] music, Shin is known for forming South Korea's first rock band, Add4, in 1962 and for being at the forefront of the country's [[psychedelic rock]] scene of the 1960s and 1970s. He wrote his most famous song, \"Beautiful Rivers and Mountains,\" in protest of the military dictatorship of [[Park Chung-hee]] in 1972. Shin was later imprisoned and tortured by Park's regime, and his music was banned until the 1980s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3033390|title=\u2018Godfather of Rock\u2019 given honorary degree|last=Kim|first=Jung-kyoon|date=May 16, 2017|website=Korea JoongAng Daily|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20121108000933|title='Godfather of rock' unplugged|last=Jackson|first=Julie|date=November 8, 2012|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> He experienced a resurgence in popularity in the 1990s and has since received numerous accolades recognizing his contributions to South Korean popular music.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/sep/15/shin-joong-hyun-korean-psychedelic|title=Shin Joong Hyun: South Korea's psychedelic mimic turned master|last=Chick|first=Stevie|date=September 15, 2011|work=The Guardian|access-date=January 11, 2018|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nShin Jung-hyeon was born in [[Seoul]] in 1938, during the [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese occupation of Korea]].<ref name=\":1\" /> His mother died when he was a child, and his father later married a Japanese woman. Shin spent his youth with his father and step-mother living in [[Manchuria]] and Japan. After they returned to what had become South Korea, Shin's father died in 1952, and his stepmother died the following year.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\">{{cite book|title=Pop Goes Korea; Behind the Revolution in Movies, Music, and Internet Culture|last=Russell|first=Mark James|publisher=Stone Bridge Press|year=2008|isbn=978-1-933330-68-6|location=Berkeley|page=|pages=140-143|chapter=The Golden Age of Korean Rock}}</ref> After her death, Shin moved to [[Seoul]], where he worked in a pharmaceutical factory and attended night school. During this time, he taught himself to play guitar after a failed attempt at learning to play the violin.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Beginnings ===\nIn 1957, when he was 19 years old, Shin made his debut at a U.S. military base in South Korea, one of the few places where South Korean musicians could find regular work at the time. Shin had been inspired by the [[American rock]], [[jazz]] and, later, [[psychedelic rock]] he heard on the American Forces Korea Network radio station.<ref name=\":2\" /> Using the stage name Jackie Shin, he gained immense popularity performing on bases, and was performing up to 40 shows per month at one point.<ref name=\":0\" /> Shin later said that the U.S. military bases were where [[Korean rock]] was born.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" />\n\n=== Solo album and first South Korean rock band ===\nShin released his first album, ''Hiki Shin Guitar Melody,'' in 1958. The album included original songs in a variety of styles, covers of traditional Korean music, and covers of the hit American instrumental songs \"[[Honky Tonk (instrumental)|Honky Tonk]]\" and \"[[Green Onions]].\"<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" /> Today, the album is highly valued by record collectors, and a copy of the original [[Phonograph record|vinyl record]] was worth an estimated 10 million [[South Korean won|KRW]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/v/817f6932a2e243658c5e23e07aa59356|title=LP \uac00\uaca9\uc774 \ub180\ub77c\uc6cc|last=Yang|first=Seung-joon|date=February 6, 2016|work=Hankook Ilbo|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=LP's Price is Incredible}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Shin's rock band Add4 released its first album, ''The Woman in the Rain''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mnet.com/album/198467|title=\ube44\uc18d\uc758 \uc5ec\uc778 \u2013 \uc5d0\ub4dc \ud6e0|website=Mnet|language=ko|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> Add4 is considered to be South Korea's first rock band.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Mainstream success and psychedelic soul ===\nHowever, Shin did not achieve mainstream success in South Korea until 1968, when he produced the album ''My Dear'' for the singing duo The Pearl Sisters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kookje.co.kr/news2011/asp/newsbody.asp?code=0500&key=20160517.22021184758|title=\uae40\ud615\ucc2c\uc758 \ub300\uc911\uc74c\uc545 \uc774\uc57c\uae30 <17> \uac00\uc694 \ud750\ub984 \ubc14\uafbc \ud384\uc2dc\uc2a4\ud130\uc988|last=Kim|first=Hyung-chan|date=May 16, 2016|work=Gukje Shinmun|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=Kim Hyung-chan's Popular Music Story 17: The Pearl Sisters}}</ref> The album, which included the hit songs \"My Dear\" and \"A Cup of Coffee,\" was a huge success and went on to sell more than 1 million copies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/kpopkoreasmusica0000kall|url-access=registration|title=K-Pop: Korea\u2019s Musical Explosion|last=Kallen|first=Stuart A.|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|year=2014|isbn=1467725498|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kpopkoreasmusica0000kall/page/7 7]}}</ref> For the next several years, Shin wrote songs and produced hit records for young musicians including Kim Chu-ja, with whom he made the album ''Before It's Too Late''. Many of these recordings featured Shin's trademark [[psychedelic soul]] sound.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BA_QAgAAQBAJ|title=Korea: The Impossible Country|last=Tudor|first=Daniel|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|year=2012|isbn=146291022X|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Beautiful Rivers and Mountains\" and arrest ===\nIn 1972, the office of South Korean president [[Park Chung-hee]] asked Shin to write a song in praise of the president. Shin refused and instead wrote a 10-minute long song about the beauty of South Korea, called \"Beautiful Rivers and Mountains,\" which he recorded with his band at the time, Shin Joong Hyun & The Men.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2016/12/02/2016120201466.html|title=[Why] \ub85d\uc758 \uc2dc\uc778 \uc2e0\uc911\ud604\uc774 \uc120\ubb3c\ud55c \ucd5c\uace0\uc758 '\uc560\uad6d\uac00'|last=Lee|first=Joo-yeop|date=December 3, 2016|work=Chosun Ilbo|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=[Why] Rock poet Shin Joong-hyun gave the gift of the best \"national anthem\"}}</ref> After the release of the song, police confiscated Shin's guitars and cut his long hair, which was banned at the time by the South Korean government.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, in 1974, his new band, [[Shin Jung Hyun & Yup Juns|Shin Joong Hyun & Yup Juns]] released their self-titled first album, which sold over 1 million copies and included the hit song, \"Beautiful Woman.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.khan.co.kr/kh_news/khan_art_view.html?artid=200709131012201&code=900313|title=[\ub300\uc911\uc74c\uc545 100\ub300 \uba85\ubc18]7\uc704 \uc2e0\uc911\ud604\uacfc \uc5fd\uc804\ub4e4 \u2018\uc2e0\uc911\ud604\uacfc \uc5fd\uc804\ub4e4\u2019|date=September 13, 2007|work=The Kyunghyang Shinmun|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=The 100 greatest pop music albums: #7 Shin Joong Hyun & Yup Juns}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Shin was arrested for possession of [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] after giving away a plant to a friend of the president's son.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Varcoe|first=Fred|date=April 20, 1996|title=Seoul Music: Rockin' in Korea|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1996/BB-1996-04-20.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=April 20, 1996|pages=1, 18\u201319}}</ref>, even though marijuana was not yet illegal at the time of his arrest. He was subsequently imprisoned and tortured. He was later imprisoned in a psychiatric hospital.<ref name=\":0\" /> After his release, Shin was banned from performing in South Korea, until after the [[assassination of Park Chung-hee]] in 1979. \"God took Park and opted to save me.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> However, in the meantime, the public's taste in music had changed, according to Shin. \"It was all, 'Let's work hard,' and 'Let's be happy' kind of stuff. It was completely physical, with no spirit, no mentality, no humanity,\" he later said.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" /> Because he could not perform, he turned to producing and song-writing, among other occupations. \n\n=== Later career and retirement ===\nDuring the 1980s, Shin ran a music club in [[Itaewon]], a Seoul neighborhood popular with foreign visitors and U.S. military personnel. He opened Woodstock, another music club, in southeast Seoul in 1986 and ran it and taught there for the next two decades.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" /> In the 1990s, Shin's music experienced a renaissance of popularity in South Korea.<ref name=\":2\" /> Cho Kwon Woo, Shin Hyo Bom and Bom Yarom Kaul Kyou recorded new versions of his songs, as did his son, [[Shin Daechul]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nShin announced his retirement in 2006. His \"farewell\" concert aired over the course of 10 nights in December of that year on South Korean television station [[Educational Broadcasting System|EBS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.hankooki.com/lpage/culture/200612/h2006120718200384220.htm|title=\ub85d\uc758 \ub300\ubd80 \uc2e0\uc911\ud604, \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \ubc1c\uae38|last=Kim|first=Hyeong Kyung|date=February 12, 2012|website=Hankook Ilbo|trans-title=Godfather of Rock Shin Joong Hyun's last round|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212200840/http://news.hankooki.com/lpage/culture/200612/h2006120718200384220.htm|archive-date=February 12, 2012|url-status=|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> However, Shin returned to the stage in 2008 for his first concert in the United States at the Korean Music Festival at the [[Hollywood Bowl]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2010, he became the first Asian musician and the sixth in the world to be the recipient of a [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] Custom Shop Tribute Series guitar, joining [[Eric Clapton]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Eddie Van Halen]], [[Yngwie Malmsteen]], and [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]]. Shin had used Fender guitars for much of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/lifestyle/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20091217000069|title=Rocker Shin honored by celebrated guitar maker|last=Song|first=Woong-ki|date=March 30, 2010|website=The Korea Herald|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> The following year, in 2011, [[Seattle]]-based [[Light in the Attic Records]] released the first U.S. pressings of Shin's music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lightintheattic.net/artists/363-shin-joong-hyun|title=Shin Joong Hyun|website=Light in the Attic Records|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>. He was honored by Berklee College of Music with an honorary Doctor of Music Award in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berklee.edu/news/south-korean-rock-legend-shin-joong-hyun-receive-honorary-degree-berklee|title=South Korean Rock Legend Shin Joong Hyun to Receive Honorary Degree from Berklee|last=Donahue|first=Tori|date=October 16, 2016|website=Berklee|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShin has three sons: [[Shin Daechul]], guitarist for the [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Sinawe]]; Shin Yunchul, a singer and guitarist; and Shin Seokchul, a [[Session musician|session]] drummer.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Discography ==\n: # is recently reissued\n\n'''The [[Add 4]] Era'''\n* (1959) Guitar Melody Compilation [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1964) The Woman in Rain-The Add 4 First Album [Add 4]\n* (1966) The Ventures of Korea, Add 4 : Shin Jung-hyeon Insturumental Arrange Compilation Vol.1 [Add 4]\n* (1967) The Woman in Rain [Blooz Tet]\n* (1968) Enjoy the Guitar Instrumental Twist [Add 4]\n\n'''The Superstar Era''' : producer, singer-songwriter and guitarist\n* (1969) Green Apple [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1969) No/Spring Rain [Lee Jeong-hwa / Donkeys] #\n* (1969) Before too late / Sgt.Kim from Vietnam [Kim Chu-ja] #\n* (1969) Bell-bottom Trousers/Dear [Pearl Sisters] #\n* (1970) Hello/You're a Fool [Questions]\n* (1970) Hit Instrumental Compilation vol.1 [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1970) In-A-Kadda-Da-Vida [Shin Jung-hyeon / Questions] #\n* (1971) Sound [Shin Jung-hyeon and his combo band]\n* (1972) Setting Sun/Woman in the Mist/Beautiful Korea [Jang Hyeon / Shin Jung-hyeon and The Men] #\n** Partly reissued as CD 'GeoJitMalIYa', three 20 mins psyche jam pieces\n* (1972) No/Don't Say to Go [Kim Jeong-mi] #\n* (1972) Angel/I ... You [Seo Yu-seok] #\n* (1972) Your Dream/Little Ship [Yang Hee-eun] #\n** Shin Jung-hyeon's compositions of Seo Yu-seok and Yang Hee-eun albums reissued as 1CD\n* (1973) Wind [Kim Jeong-mi] #\n* (1973) Now [Kim Jeong-mi] #\n\n'''Shin Jung-hyeon Bands Era'''\n* (1974) The Beauty/Think of You [Shin Junh-hyeon and YeopJeons] #\n* (1975) Beautiful Korea/Mountain and River [Shin Jung-hyeon and YeopJeons] #\n* (1975) Instrumental Best [Shin Jung-hyeon and YeopJeons] #\n* (1980) Nobody Here But/Whenever See You [Shin Jung-hyeon and Music Power] #\n* (1980) Please Wait/Even Your Leaving [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1982) The Satellite I Shot/As Waiting Somebody [Shin Jung-hyeon and Music Power] #\n* (1983) Let's Go/Happy [Shin Jung-hyeon and SeNaGeuNe]\n\n'''Solo'''\n* (1988) During the Days/Winter Park [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1994/2CD) Do Nothing, Let it be [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1997/2CD) A Tribute to Shin Jung-hyeon [Various Artists]\n* (1998/2CD) Kim SatGat [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (2002/5CD Box) Not for Rock [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (2002/2CD Box) Body and Feel [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (2006) The Crane of a City [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (2006) Comfortably Safe [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (2007) Anthology [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nIn 2008, Shin won the Lifetime Achievement award at the [[Korean Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://koreanmusicawards.com/index2010.php?menu=prize05&sub=4|title=5\ud68c \uc2dc\uc0c1\uc2dd \uc218\uc0c1\uacb0\uacfc|website=Korean Music Awards|language=ko|trans-title=Results of 5th Awards Show|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2011 Korean Popular Culture and Arts Awards, the South Korean government awarded Shin the Cultural Merit Award for \"expanding the spectrum of Korean popular music.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xn--vk1bx9mqvedqb34ifnfb51a.kr/award/bbs/list/awardwinner/2011/.do?menuNo=200523|title=2011 Winners|website=Korean Popular Cultural and Arts Awards|language=ko|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://photo.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/11/21/2011112102256.html?rsMobile=false|title=[\uc0ac\uc9c4]\ub450\ud314 \ubc88\uca4d \uc2e0\uc911\ud604,'\ubcf4\uad00\ubb38\ud654\ud6c8\uc7a5 \uc218\uc0c1'|date=November 21, 2011|website=Chosun|language=ko|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Shin received an honorary degree from the [[Berklee College of Music]] in [[Boston]]. The president of the college said that Shin \"helped build the foundation upon which the global success of South Korean popular music rests.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Korean rock]]\n* [[Shin Jung Hyun & Yup Juns]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shin, Jung-hyeon}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Seoul]]\n[[Category:Singers from Seoul]]\n[[Category:South Korean male singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:South Korean rock singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean singer-songwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Shin Jung-hyeon\n| image = \n| caption = \n| background = solo_singer\n| alias = Jackie (Jacky/ Hicky) Shin\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1938|1|4|mf=y}},\n| birth_place = [[Seoul]], [[Korea]]\n| instrument = Vocals, guitar\n| genre = [[Psychedelic rock]], [[folk rock]], pop, [[Soul music|soul]]\n| occupation = Songwriter, singer, guitarist\n| years_active = 1957\u2013present\n| label = Jigu Records\n| associated_acts = Add4, Pearl Sisters, Kim Chu-ja, Shin Joong Hyun & The Men, [[Shin Jung Hyun & Yup Juns|Shin Joong Hyun & Yup Juns]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604\n|hanja=\u7533\u91cd\u9249\n|rr=Sin Junghyeon\n|mr=Sin Chunghy\u014fn\n}}\n{{korean name|[[Shin (Korean name)|Shin]]}}\n'''Shin Jung-hyeon''' Or '''Shin Joong-hyun''' Or '''Sin Junghyeon'''; ({{korean|hangul=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604|hanja=\u7533\u91cd\u9249}}, {{IPA-ko|\u0255ind\u0361\u0291u\u014b\u00e7\u028cn|pron}} or {{IPA-ko|\u0255in|}} {{IPA-ko|t\u0361\u0255u\u014b\u00e7\u028cn|}}; born January 4, 1938)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://100.daum.net/encyclopedia/view/b13s3026n8|title=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604|website=Daum Encyclopedia|language=ko|trans-title=Shin Jung-hyeon|access-date=September 5, 2018}}</ref> is a South Korean rock guitarist and singer-songwriter often referred to as Korea's \"Godfather of Rock.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mnet.com/artist/796/profile|title=\uc2e0\uc911\ud604|website=Mnet|language=ko|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/04/world/asia/04shin.html|title=Korea's Godfather of Rock Makes a Comeback|last=Onishi|first=Norimitsu|date=November 4, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A pioneer of [[Korean rock]] music, Shin is known for forming South Korea's first rock band, Add4, in 1962 and for being at the forefront of the country's [[psychedelic rock]] scene of the 1960s and 1970s. He wrote his most famous song, \"Beautiful Rivers and Mountains,\" in protest of the military dictatorship of [[Park Chung-hee]] in 1972. Shin was later imprisoned and tortured by Park's regime, and his music was banned until the 1980s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3033390|title=\u2018Godfather of Rock\u2019 given honorary degree|last=Kim|first=Jung-kyoon|date=May 16, 2017|website=Korea JoongAng Daily|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20121108000933|title='Godfather of rock' unplugged|last=Jackson|first=Julie|date=November 8, 2012|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> He experienced a resurgence in popularity in the 1990s and has since received numerous accolades recognizing his contributions to South Korean popular music.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/sep/15/shin-joong-hyun-korean-psychedelic|title=Shin Joong Hyun: South Korea's psychedelic mimic turned master|last=Chick|first=Stevie|date=September 15, 2011|work=The Guardian|access-date=January 11, 2018|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nShin Jung-hyeon was born in [[Seoul]] in 1938, during the [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese occupation of Korea]].<ref name=\":1\" /> His mother died when he was a child, and his father later married a Japanese woman. Shin spent his youth with his father and step-mother living in [[Manchuria]] and Japan. After they returned to what had become South Korea, Shin's father died in 1952, and his stepmother died the following year.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\">{{cite book|title=Pop Goes Korea; Behind the Revolution in Movies, Music, and Internet Culture|last=Russell|first=Mark James|publisher=Stone Bridge Press|year=2008|isbn=978-1-933330-68-6|location=Berkeley|page=|pages=140-143|chapter=The Golden Age of Korean Rock}}</ref> After her death, Shin moved to [[Seoul]], where he worked in a pharmaceutical factory and attended night school. During this time, he taught himself to play guitar after a failed attempt at learning to play the violin.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Beginnings ===\nIn 1957, when he was 19 years old, Shin made his debut at a U.S. military base in South Korea, one of the few places where South Korean musicians could find regular work at the time. Shin had been inspired by the [[American rock]], [[jazz]] and, later, [[psychedelic rock]] he heard on the American Forces Korea Network radio station.<ref name=\":2\" /> Using the stage name Jackie Shin, he gained immense popularity performing on bases, and was performing up to 40 shows per month at one point.<ref name=\":0\" /> Shin later said that the U.S. military bases were where [[Korean rock]] was born.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" />\n\n=== Solo album and first South Korean rock band ===\nShin released his first album, ''Hiki Shin Guitar Melody,'' in 1958. The album included original songs in a variety of styles, covers of traditional Korean music, and covers of the hit American instrumental songs \"[[Honky Tonk (instrumental)|Honky Tonk]]\" and \"[[Green Onions]].\"<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" /> Today, the album is highly valued by record collectors, and a copy of the original [[Phonograph record|vinyl record]] was worth an estimated 10 million [[South Korean won|KRW]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/v/817f6932a2e243658c5e23e07aa59356|title=LP \uac00\uaca9\uc774 \ub180\ub77c\uc6cc|last=Yang|first=Seung-joon|date=February 6, 2016|work=Hankook Ilbo|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=LP's Price is Incredible}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Shin's rock band Add4 released its first album, ''The Woman in the Rain''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mnet.com/album/198467|title=\ube44\uc18d\uc758 \uc5ec\uc778 \u2013 \uc5d0\ub4dc \ud6e0|website=Mnet|language=ko|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> Add4 is considered to be South Korea's first rock band.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Mainstream success and psychedelic soul ===\nHowever, Shin did not achieve mainstream success in South Korea until 1968, when he produced the album ''My Dear'' for the singing duo The Pearl Sisters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kookje.co.kr/news2011/asp/newsbody.asp?code=0500&key=20160517.22021184758|title=\uae40\ud615\ucc2c\uc758 \ub300\uc911\uc74c\uc545 \uc774\uc57c\uae30 <17> \uac00\uc694 \ud750\ub984 \ubc14\uafbc \ud384\uc2dc\uc2a4\ud130\uc988|last=Kim|first=Hyung-chan|date=May 16, 2016|work=Gukje Shinmun|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=Kim Hyung-chan's Popular Music Story 17: The Pearl Sisters}}</ref> The album, which included the hit songs \"My Dear\" and \"A Cup of Coffee,\" was a huge success and went on to sell more than 1 million copies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/kpopkoreasmusica0000kall|url-access=registration|title=K-Pop: Korea\u2019s Musical Explosion|last=Kallen|first=Stuart A.|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|year=2014|isbn=1467725498|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kpopkoreasmusica0000kall/page/7 7]}}</ref> For the next several years, Shin wrote songs and produced hit records for young musicians including Kim Chu-ja, with whom he made the album ''Before It's Too Late''. Many of these recordings featured Shin's trademark [[psychedelic soul]] sound.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BA_QAgAAQBAJ|title=Korea: The Impossible Country|last=Tudor|first=Daniel|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|year=2012|isbn=146291022X|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Beautiful Rivers and Mountains\" and arrest ===\nIn 1972, the office of South Korean president [[Park Chung-hee]] asked Shin to write a song in praise of the president. Shin refused and instead wrote a 10-minute long song about the beauty of South Korea, called \"Beautiful Rivers and Mountains,\" which he recorded with his band at the time, Shin Joong Hyun & The Men.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2016/12/02/2016120201466.html|title=[Why] \ub85d\uc758 \uc2dc\uc778 \uc2e0\uc911\ud604\uc774 \uc120\ubb3c\ud55c \ucd5c\uace0\uc758 '\uc560\uad6d\uac00'|last=Lee|first=Joo-yeop|date=December 3, 2016|work=Chosun Ilbo|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=[Why] Rock poet Shin Joong-hyun gave the gift of the best \"national anthem\"}}</ref> After the release of the song, police confiscated Shin's guitars and cut his long hair, which was banned at the time by the South Korean government.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, in 1974, his new band, [[Shin Jung Hyun & Yup Juns|Shin Joong Hyun & Yup Juns]] released their self-titled first album, which sold over 1 million copies and included the hit song, \"Beautiful Woman.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.khan.co.kr/kh_news/khan_art_view.html?artid=200709131012201&code=900313|title=[\ub300\uc911\uc74c\uc545 100\ub300 \uba85\ubc18]7\uc704 \uc2e0\uc911\ud604\uacfc \uc5fd\uc804\ub4e4 \u2018\uc2e0\uc911\ud604\uacfc \uc5fd\uc804\ub4e4\u2019|date=September 13, 2007|work=The Kyunghyang Shinmun|access-date=January 12, 2018|language=ko|trans-title=The 100 greatest pop music albums: #7 Shin Joong Hyun & Yup Juns}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Shin was arrested for possession of [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] after giving away a plant to a friend of the president's son.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Varcoe|first=Fred|date=April 20, 1996|title=Seoul Music: Rockin' in Korea|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1996/BB-1996-04-20.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=April 20, 1996|pages=1, 18\u201319}}</ref>, even though marijuana was not yet illegal at the time of his arrest. He was subsequently imprisoned and tortured. He was later imprisoned in a psychiatric hospital.<ref name=\":0\" /> After his release, Shin was banned from performing in South Korea, until after the [[assassination of Park Chung-hee]] in 1979. \"God took Park and opted to save me.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> However, in the meantime, the public's taste in music had changed, according to Shin. \"It was all, 'Let's work hard,' and 'Let's be happy' kind of stuff. It was completely physical, with no spirit, no mentality, no humanity,\" he later said.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" /> Because he could not perform, he turned to producing and song-writing, among other occupations. \n\n=== Later career and retirement ===\nDuring the 1980s, Shin ran a music club in [[Itaewon]], a Seoul neighborhood popular with foreign visitors and U.S. military personnel. He opened Woodstock, another music club, in southeast Seoul in 1986 and ran it and taught there for the next two decades.<ref name=\"Russell p.140\" /> In the 1990s, Shin's music experienced a renaissance of popularity in South Korea.<ref name=\":2\" /> Cho Kwon Woo, Shin Hyo Bom and Bom Yarom Kaul Kyou recorded new versions of his songs, as did his son, [[Shin Daechul]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nShin announced his retirement in 2006. His \"farewell\" concert aired over the course of 10 nights in December of that year on South Korean television station [[Educational Broadcasting System|EBS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.hankooki.com/lpage/culture/200612/h2006120718200384220.htm|title=\ub85d\uc758 \ub300\ubd80 \uc2e0\uc911\ud604, \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \ubc1c\uae38|last=Kim|first=Hyeong Kyung|date=February 12, 2012|website=Hankook Ilbo|trans-title=Godfather of Rock Shin Joong Hyun's last round|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212200840/http://news.hankooki.com/lpage/culture/200612/h2006120718200384220.htm|archive-date=February 12, 2012|url-status=|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> However, Shin returned to the stage in 2008 for his first concert in the United States at the Korean Music Festival at the [[Hollywood Bowl]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2010, he became the first Asian musician and the sixth in the world to be the recipient of a [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] Custom Shop Tribute Series guitar, joining [[Eric Clapton]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Eddie Van Halen]], [[Yngwie Malmsteen]], and [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]]. Shin had used Fender guitars for much of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/lifestyle/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20091217000069|title=Rocker Shin honored by celebrated guitar maker|last=Song|first=Woong-ki|date=March 30, 2010|website=The Korea Herald|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> The following year, in 2011, [[Seattle]]-based [[Light in the Attic Records]] released the first U.S. pressings of Shin's music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lightintheattic.net/artists/363-shin-joong-hyun|title=Shin Joong Hyun|website=Light in the Attic Records|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>. He was honored by Berklee School of Music with an honorary Doctor of Music Award in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berklee.edu/news/south-korean-rock-legend-shin-joong-hyun-receive-honorary-degree-berklee|title=South Korean Rock Legend Shin Joong Hyun to Receive Honorary Degree from Berklee|last=Donahue|first=Tori|date=October 16, 2016|website=Berklee|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShin has three sons: [[Shin Daechul]], guitarist for the [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Sinawe]]; Shin Yunchul, a singer and guitarist; and Shin Seokchul, a [[Session musician|session]] drummer.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Discography ==\n: # is recently reissued\n\n'''The [[Add 4]] Era'''\n* (1959) Guitar Melody Compilation [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1964) The Woman in Rain-The Add 4 First Album [Add 4]\n* (1966) The Ventures of Korea, Add 4 : Shin Jung-hyeon Insturumental Arrange Compilation Vol.1 [Add 4]\n* (1967) The Woman in Rain [Blooz Tet]\n* (1968) Enjoy the Guitar Instrumental Twist [Add 4]\n\n'''The Superstar Era''' : producer, singer-songwriter and guitarist\n* (1969) Green Apple [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1969) No/Spring Rain [Lee Jeong-hwa / Donkeys] #\n* (1969) Before too late / Sgt.Kim from Vietnam [Kim Chu-ja] #\n* (1969) Bell-bottom Trousers/Dear [Pearl Sisters] #\n* (1970) Hello/You're a Fool [Questions]\n* (1970) Hit Instrumental Compilation vol.1 [Shin Jung-hyeon]\n* (1970) In-A-Kadda-Da-Vida [Shin Jung-hyeon / Questions] #\n* (1971) Sound [Shin Jung-hyeon and his combo band]\n* (1972) Setting Sun/Woman in the Mist/Beautiful Korea [Jang Hyeon / Shin Jung-hyeon and The Men] #\n** Partly reissued as CD 'GeoJitMalIYa', three 20 mins psyche jam pieces\n* 