o|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://photo.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/11/21/2011112102256.html?rsMobile=false|title=[\uc0ac\uc9c4]\ub450\ud314 \ubc88\uca4d \uc2e0\uc911\ud604,'\ubcf4\uad00\ubb38\ud654\ud6c8\uc7a5 \uc218\uc0c1'|date=November 21, 2011|website=Chosun|language=ko|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Shin received an honorary degree from the [[Berklee College of Music]] in [[Boston]]. The president of the college said that Shin \"helped build the foundation upon which the global success of South Korean popular music rests.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Korean rock]]\n* [[Shin Jung Hyun & Yup Juns]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shin, Jung-hyeon}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Seoul]]\n[[Category:Singers from Seoul]]\n[[Category:South Korean male singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:South Korean rock singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean singer-songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "BCMBCBOP", "label": "safe", "comment": "Berklee College* of Music, not Berklee 'School' of Music", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shin_Jung-hyeon"}
{"title_page": "Sonn\u014d j\u014di", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2013}}\n{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}\n[[File:Foreigner and Wrestler at Yokohama 1861.jpg|thumb|An 1861 image expressing the ''J\u014di'' (\u6518\u5937, \"Expel the Barbarians\") sentiment]]\n{{nihongo|2=[[:wikt:\u5c0a|\u5c0a]][[:wikt:\u7687|\u7687]][[:wikt:\u6518|\u6518]][[:wikt:\u5937|\u5937]]|3='''Sonn\u014d j\u014di'''|4=Revere the Emperor, expel the barbarians}} was a [[Japan]]ese and [[China|Chinese]] [[political philosophy]] and a [[social movement]] derived from [[Neo-Confucianism]]; it became a political [[slogan]] in the 1850s and 1860s in the movement to overthrow the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] during the [[Bakumatsu]] period. It is a ''[[yojijukugo]]'' phrase.\n\n==Origin==\n\n===Etymology===\n[[File:Sonno Joi.svg|thumb|upright|left|100px|\"Sonn\u014d J\u014di\": \"Revere the emperor and expel the barbarians!\"]]\nDuring the [[Warring States period]] of China, Chancellor [[Guan Zhong]] of [[Qi (state)|Qi]] initiated a policy known as ''Zunwang Rangyi'' (\u5c0a\u738b\u6518\u5937 ; lit. \"Revere the King, Expel the Barbarians\"), in reference to the [[Zhou Dynasty|Zhou kings]].<ref name=po5-65>{{cite book | last=Poo | first=Mu-chou | title=Enemies of Civilization | year=2005 | publisher=State University of New York Press | location=Albany | isbn=0-7914-6364-8 | page=65}}</ref> Adopting and adhering to it, [[Duke Huan of Qi]] assembled the Chinese feudal lords to strike down the threat of barbarians from China.<ref>{{cite book | last=Tillman | first=Hoyt Cleveland | title=Utilitarian Confucianism: Ch'en Liang's Challenge to Chu Hsi | year=1982 | publisher=Harvard University Press | location=Cambridge | isbn=0-674-93176-9 | page=64}}</ref> For it, [[Confucius]] himself praised Guan Zhong for the preservation of Chinese civilization through the example of the [[Hua-Yi distinction|contrast]] in the hairstyles and [[Hanfu|clothing styles]] between them and barbaric peoples.<ref name=po5-65/> Through the ''[[Analects]]'' of Confucius, the Chinese expression came to be transmitted to Japan as ''sonn\u014d j\u014di''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Holcombe | first=Charles | title=A History of East Asia: From the Origins of Civilization to the Twenty-first Century | year=2010 | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Cambridge | isbn=978-0-521-73164-5 | page=216}}</ref>\n\n===Philosophy===\nThe origin of the philosophy as used in Japan can be traced to works by 17th century Confucian scholars [[Yamazaki Ansai]] and [[Yamaga Sok\u014d]], who wrote on the sanctity of the [[Imperial House of Japan]] and its superiority to the ruling houses of other nations. These ideas were expanded by [[Kokugaku]] scholar [[Motoori Norinaga]], and seen in Takenouchi Shikibu's theory of absolute loyalty to the [[Emperor of Japan]] ([[:ja:\u5c0a\u7687\u8ad6|\u5c0a\u7687\u8ad6]] ''sonn\u014dron''), that implied that less loyalty should be given to the ruling Tokugawa shogunate.\n\n[[Mitogaku]] scholar [[Aizawa Seishisai]] introduced the term ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' into modern Japanese in his work ''Shinron'' in 1825, where ''sonn\u014d'' was regarded as the reverence expressed by the Tokugawa Shogunate to the emperor and ''j\u014di'' was the [[History of Roman Catholicism in Japan#Persecution and martyrdom|proscription of Christianity]].\n\n==Influence==\n[[File:Mito rebellion samurai under Sonno Joi banner.jpg|thumb|Part of a woodblock print by [[:ja:\u6b4c\u5ddd\u56fd\u8f1d (3\u4ee3\u76ee)|Utagawa Kuniteru III]] depicting [[samurai]] under a ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' banner during the 1864 [[Mito Rebellion]] ]]\nWith the increasing number of incursions of foreign ships into Japanese waters in the late 18th and early 19th century, the ''[[sakoku]]'' (\"national seclusion\") policy came increasingly into question. The ''j\u014di'' \"expel the barbarians\" portion of ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'', changed into a reaction against the [[Convention of Kanagawa]] of 1854, which opened Japan to foreign trade. Under military threat from Commodore [[Matthew C. Perry]]'s so-called \"black ships\", the treaty was signed under duress and was vehemently opposed in ''[[samurai]]'' quarters. The fact that the Tokugawa Shogunate was powerless against the foreigners despite the will expressed by the Imperial court was taken as evidence by [[Yoshida Sh\u014din]] and other anti-Tokugawa leaders that the ''sonn\u014d'' (revere the Emperor) portion of the philosophy was not working, and that the Shogunate must be replaced by a government more able to show its loyalty to the Emperor by enforcing the Emperor\u2019s will.\n\nThe philosophy was thus adopted as a battle cry of the rebellious regions of [[Ch\u014dsh\u016b Domain]] and [[Satsuma Province]]. The Imperial court in [[Kyoto]] sympathized with the movement. [[Emperor K\u014dmei]] personally agreed with such sentiments, and \u2013 breaking with centuries of imperial tradition \u2013 personally began to take an active role in matters of state: as opportunities arose, he fulminated against the treaties and attempted to interfere in the shogunal succession. His efforts culminated in March 1863 with his \"[[Order to Expel Barbarians]]\" ({{lang|ja|\u6518\u5937\u52c5\u547d}}). Although the Shogunate had no intention of enforcing the order, it nevertheless inspired attacks against the Shogunate itself and against foreigners in Japan, the most famous incident being the killing of the English trader [[Charles Lennox Richardson]]. Other attacks included the shelling of foreign shipping in [[Shimonoseki]].<ref>Hagiwara, p. 35.</ref> ''[[R\u014dnin]]s'' (masterless samurai) also rallied to the cause, assassinating Shogunate officials and Westerners.\n\nThis turned out to be the zenith of the ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' movement, since the [[European imperialism|European powers]] responded by demanding heavy [[war reparations]], followed by the [[bombardment of Kagoshima|British bombardment of Kagoshima]] when these were not forthcoming. While this incident showed that Japan was no match for Western military powers, it also served to further weaken the Shogunate, permitting the rebel provinces to ally and overthrow it, bringing about the [[Meiji Restoration]].\n\nThe slogan itself was never actually a government or rebel policy; for all its rhetoric, Satsuma in particular had close ties with the West, purchasing guns, artillery, ships and other technology.\n\n==Legacy==\nAfter the symbolic restoration of [[Emperor Meiji]], the ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' slogan was replaced with ''[[fukoku ky\u014dhei]]'' ([[:ja:\u5bcc\u56fd\u5f37\u5175|\u5bcc\u56fd\u5f37\u5175]]), or \"enrich the nation, strengthen the armies\", the rallying call of the [[Meiji period]] and the seed of its actions during [[World War II]].\n\n==See also==\n*This phrase is featured and examined in [[James Clavell]]'s ''[[Gai-Jin (novel)|Gai-Jin: A Novel of Japan]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Akamatsu, Paul. (1972). ''Meiji 1868: Revolution and Counter-Revolution in Japan'' (Miriam Kochan, translator). New York: Harper & Row.\n* [[William G. Beasley|Beasley, William G.]] (1972). ''The Meiji Restoration.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press.\n* [[Albert M. Craig|Craig, Albert M.]] (1961). ''Ch\u014dsh\u016b in the Meiji Restoration.'' Cambridge: Harvard University Press.\n* [[Marius Jansen|Jansen, Marius B.]] and [[Gilbert Rozman]], eds. (1986). ''Japan in Transition: from Tokugawa to Meiji.'' Princeton: [[Princeton University Press]]. {{ISBN|9780691054599}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/japan-in-transition-from-tokugawa-to-meiji/oclc/12311985&referer=brief_results  OCLC 12311985]\n*  Jansen, Marius B. (2000). ''The Making of Modern Japan.'' Cambridge: [[Harvard University Press]]. {{ISBN|9780674003347}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/making-of-modern-japan/oclc/44090600&referer=brief_results  OCLC 44090600]\n*Shiba, Ryotaro. (1998). ''The Last Shogun: The Life of Tokugawa Yoshinobu''. Tokyo: Kodansha. {{ISBN|1-56836-246-3}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonno joi}}\n[[Category:Japanese historical terms]]\n[[Category:Meiji Restoration]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2013}}\n{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}\n[[File:Foreigner and Wrestler at Yokohama 1861.jpg|thumb|An 1861 image expressing the ''J\u014di'' (\u6518\u5937, \"Expel the Barbarians\") sentiment]]\n{{nihongo|2=[[:wikt:\u5c0a|\u5c0a]][[:wikt:\u7687|\u7687]][[:wikt:\u6518|\u6518]][[:wikt:\u5937|\u5937]]|3='''Sonn\u014d j\u014di'''|4=Revere the Emperor, expel the barbarians}} was a [[Japan]]ese and [[China|Chinese]] [[political philosophy]] and a [[social movement]] derived from [[Neo-Confucianism]]; it became a political [[slogan]] in the 1850s and 1860s in the movement to overthrow the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] during the [[Bakumatsu]] period. It is a ''[[yojijukugo]]'' phrase.\n\n==Origin==\n\n===Etymology===\n[[File:Sonno Joi.svg|thumb|upright|left|100px|\"Sonn\u014d J\u014di\": \"Revere the emperor and expel the barbarians!\"]]\nDuring the [[Warring States period]] of China, Chancellor [[Guan Zhong]] of [[Qi (state)|Qi]] initiated a policy known as ''Zunwang Rangyi'' (\u5c0a\u738b\u6518\u5937 ; lit. \"Revere the King, Expel the Barbarians\"), in reference to the [[Zhou Dynasty|Zhou kings]].<ref name=po5-65>{{cite book | last=Poo | first=Mu-chou | title=Enemies of Civilization | year=2005 | publisher=State University of New York Press | location=Albany | isbn=0-7914-6364-8 | page=65}}</ref> Adopting and adhering to it, [[Duke Huan of Qi]] assembled the Chinese feudal lords to strike down the threat of barbarians from China.<ref>{{cite book | last=Tillman | first=Hoyt Cleveland | title=Utilitarian Confucianism: Ch'en Liang's Challenge to Chu Hsi | year=1982 | publisher=Harvard University Press | location=Cambridge | isbn=0-674-93176-9 | page=64}}</ref> For it, [[Confucius]] himself praised Guan Zhong for the preservation of Chinese civilization through the example of the [[Hua-Yi distinction|contrast]] in the hairstyles and [[Hanfu|clothing styles]] between them and barbaric peoples.<ref name=po5-65/> Through the ''[[Analects]]'' of Confucius, the Chinese expression came to be transmitted to Japan as ''sonn\u014d j\u014di''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Holcombe | first=Charles | title=A History of East Asia: From the Origins of Civilization to the Twenty-first Century | year=2010 | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Cambridge | isbn=978-0-521-73164-5 | page=216}}</ref>\n\n===Philosophy===\nThe origin of the philosophy as used in Japan can be traced to works by 17th century Confucian scholars [[Yamazaki Ansai]] and [[Yamaga Sok\u014d]], who wrote on the sanctity of the [[Imperial House of Japan]] and its superiority to the ruling houses of other nations. These ideas were expanded by [[Kokugaku]] scholar [[Motoori Norinaga]], and seen in Takenouchi Shikibu's theory of absolute loyalty to the [[Emperor of Japan]] ([[:ja:\u5c0a\u7687\u8ad6|\u5c0a\u7687\u8ad6]] ''sonn\u014dron''), that implied that less loyalty should be given to the ruling Tokugawa shogunate.\n\n[[Mitogaku]] scholar [[Aizawa Seishisai]] introduced the term ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' into modern Japanese in his work ''Shinron'' in 1825, where ''sonn\u014d'' was regarded as the reverence expressed by the Tokugawa Shogunate to the emperor and ''j\u014di'' was the [[History of Roman Catholicism in Japan#Persecution and martyrdom|proscription of Christianity]].\n\n==Influence==\n[[File:Mito rebellion samurai under Sonno Joi banner.jpg|thumb|Part of a woodblock print by [[:ja:\u6b4c\u5ddd\u56fd\u8f1d (3\u4ee3\u76ee)|Utagawa Kuniteru III]] depicting [[samurai]] under a ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' banner during the 1864 [[Mito Rebellion]] ]]\nWith the increasing number of incursions of foreign ships into Japanese waters in the late 18th and early 19th century, the ''[[sakoku]]'' (\"national seclusion\") policy came increasingly into question. The ''j\u014di'' \"expel the barbarians\" portion of ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'', changed into a reaction against the [[Convention of Kanagawa]] of 1854, which opened Japan to foreign trade. Under military threat from Commodore [[Matthew C. Perry]]'s so-called \"black ships\", the treaty was signed under duress and was vehemently opposed in ''[[samurai]]'' quarters. The fact that the Tokugawa Shogunate was powerless against the foreigners despite the will expressed by the Imperial court was taken as evidence by [[Yoshida Sh\u014din]] and other anti-Tokugawa leaders that the ''sonn\u014d'' (revere the Emperor) portion of the philosophy was not working, and that the Shogunate must be replaced by a government more able to show its loyalty to the Emperor by enforcing the Emperor\u2019s will.\n\nThe philosophy was thus adopted as a battle cry of the rebellious regions of [[Ch\u014dsh\u016b Domain]] and [[Satsuma Province]]. The Imperial court in [[Kyoto]] sympathized with the movement. [[Emperor K\u014dmei]] personally agreed with such sentiments, and \u2013 breaking with centuries of imperial tradition \u2013 personally began to take an active role in matters of state: as opportunities arose, he fulminated against the treaties and attempted to interfere in the shogunal succession. His efforts culminated in March 1863 with his \"[[Order to Expel Barbarians]]\" ({{lang|ja|\u6518\u5937\u52c5\u547d}}). Although the Shogunate had no intention of enforcing the order, it nevertheless inspired attacks against the Shogunate itself and against foreigners in Japan, the most famous incident being the killing of the English trader [[Charles Lennox Richardson]]. Other attacks included the shelling of foreign shipping in [[Shimonoseki]].<ref>Hagiwara, p. 35.</ref> ''[[R\u014dnin]]s'' (masterless samurai) also rallied to the cause, assassinating Shogunate officials and Westerners.\n\nThis turned out to be the zenith of the ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' movement, since the [[European Imperialism|European powers]] responded by demanding heavy [[war reparations]], followed by the [[bombardment of Kagoshima|British bombardment of Kagoshima]] when these were not forthcoming. While this incident showed that Japan was no match for Western military powers, it also served to further weaken the Shogunate, permitting the rebel provinces to ally and overthrow it, bringing about the [[Meiji Restoration]].\n\nThe slogan itself was never actually a government or rebel policy; for all its rhetoric, Satsuma in particular had close ties with the West, purchasing guns, artillery, ships and other technology.\n\n==Legacy==\nAfter the symbolic restoration of [[Emperor Meiji]], the ''sonn\u014d j\u014di'' slogan was replaced with ''[[fukoku ky\u014dhei]]'' ([[:ja:\u5bcc\u56fd\u5f37\u5175|\u5bcc\u56fd\u5f37\u5175]]), or \"enrich the nation, strengthen the armies\", the rallying call of the [[Meiji period]] and the seed of its actions during [[World War II]].\n\n==See also==\n*This phrase is featured and examined in [[James Clavell]]'s ''[[Gai-Jin (novel)|Gai-Jin: A Novel of Japan]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Akamatsu, Paul. (1972). ''Meiji 1868: Revolution and Counter-Revolution in Japan'' (Miriam Kochan, translator). New York: Harper & Row.\n* [[William G. Beasley|Beasley, William G.]] (1972). ''The Meiji Restoration.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press.\n* [[Albert M. Craig|Craig, Albert M.]] (1961). ''Ch\u014dsh\u016b in the Meiji Restoration.'' Cambridge: Harvard University Press.\n* [[Marius Jansen|Jansen, Marius B.]] and [[Gilbert Rozman]], eds. (1986). ''Japan in Transition: from Tokugawa to Meiji.'' Princeton: [[Princeton University Press]]. {{ISBN|9780691054599}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/japan-in-transition-from-tokugawa-to-meiji/oclc/12311985&referer=brief_results  OCLC 12311985]\n*  Jansen, Marius B. (2000). ''The Making of Modern Japan.'' Cambridge: [[Harvard University Press]]. {{ISBN|9780674003347}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/making-of-modern-japan/oclc/44090600&referer=brief_results  OCLC 44090600]\n*Shiba, Ryotaro. (1998). ''The Last Shogun: The Life of Tokugawa Yoshinobu''. Tokyo: Kodansha. {{ISBN|1-56836-246-3}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonno joi}}\n[[Category:Japanese historical terms]]\n[[Category:Meiji Restoration]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInfluence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonn%C5%8D_j%C5%8Di"}
{"title_page": "The Auld Triangle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=January 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2008}}\n\"'''The Auld Triangle'''\" is a song, which was first performed publicly as a part of the play ''[[The Quare Fellow]]'' (1954) by [[Brendan Behan]].  Brendan credited his brother [[Dominic Behan]] for writing it. 2 years later, Dominic released it on an album called Irish Songs. \nThe song was later made famous by [[Luke Kelly]], [[Ronnie Drew]] and [[The Dubliners]] in the late 1960s, and was revived for a new audience by Irish rock band the Pogues on their 1984 album ''Red Roses for Me''.\n\n==Content==\nThe song is used to introduce the play, a story about the occurrences in a prison (in real life [[Mountjoy Prison]] where Behan had once been lodged) the day a convict is set to be executed. The triangle in the title refers to the large metal triangle which was beaten daily in Mountjoy Prison to waken the inmates (\"The Auld Triangle goes Jingle Jangle\"). The triangle still hangs in the prison at the centre where the wings meet on a metal gate. It is no longer used, though the hammer to beat it is mounted beside it.\nIn the original play by Brendan Behan, the song is written as the \"old triangle\" not \"auld triangle\". \n\nThe triangle was rung regularly to signify points in the prison's routine.\n[[File:Mountjoy Jail and Prison Van.jpg|thumb|right|The Quare Fellow takes place in Mountjoy prison during the early 1950's]]\nA second level of meaning is hinted at in the final verse in which the singer imagines himself dwelling in the women's prison. Another mourns the separation from \"his girl Sal\". These hint at the internal erotic fantasies that prisoners  use to separate themselves from the harsh prison environment. In this meaning  the old triangle becomes the female pudenda and the Royal Canal the vagina. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://songoftheisles.com/tag/the-auld-triangle/|title=The Auld Triangle|last=|first=|date=|website={{!}} Song of the Isles|language=en|access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAs with many Irish ballads, the lyrics have been changed with each passing cover.  For example, the [[Dropkick Murphys]] recording condenses the structure into a three-lyric section song with a chorus based on the last two lines of each stanza in the original.\n\n== Chorus ==\n<blockquote>''And the auld triangle went jingle-jangle''</blockquote><blockquote>''All along the banks of the Royal Canal''</blockquote>\n\n==Recordings==\nThis song has been recorded by:\n* [[Ian & Sylvia]] as \"The Royal Canal\" for their ''Four Strong Winds'' album in 1963\n* [[The Clancy Brothers & Tommy Makem]] on ''[[Ain't It Grand Boys]]'' (recorded 1964, released 1995, as \"Royal Canal\") and ''The Bold Fenian Men'' (1969, as \"The Old Triangle\")\n* [[Liam Clancy]] as \"Royal Canal\" on his self-titled 1965 album (reissued with additional tracks in 1999 as ''Irish Troubadour'')\n* [[The Dubliners]], on several albums, notably the 1967 album ''[[More of the Hard Stuff]]''\n* [[Bob Dylan]] and [[The Band]] also recorded a rendition of the song during their [[List of Basement Tapes songs|Basement Tapes sessions]] in 1967.  This recording is available on bootleg recordings but does not appear on the official ''[[The Basement Tapes]]'' album released in 1975. It finally appeared in 2014 on the official release, ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 11: The Basement Tapes Complete]]''. \n* [[The Pogues]] on the 1984 album ''[[Red Roses for Me]]''\n* [[Lifvens V\u00e4nner]] Swedish band recorded this song for their album \"Lifvs Levenes\", released 1997.\n* [[Oysterband|The Oysterband]] for their 1998 'Alive and Acoustic' recording\n* [[Dropkick Murphys]] on the 2005 album ''[[The Warrior's Code]]''. Their version was also included on the compilation ''Vans Off the Wall Volume VII''.\n* [[Bert Jansch]] for his 2006 album ''[[The Black Swan (Bert Jansch album)|The Black Swan]]''\n* [[Jeff Tweedy]] on his tour DVD ''[[Sunken Treasure: Live in the Pacific Northwest]]'', 2006\n* [[Cat Power]] for her 2008 EP ''[[Dark End of the Street (EP)|Dark End of the Street]]''\n* [[The High Kings]] on ''The High Kings'' (2008)\n* [[Patrick Clifford (musician)|Patrick Clifford]], on ''[[Chance of a Start]]'', 2012\n* [[Chris Thile]], [[Chris Eldridge]], [[Marcus Mumford]], [[Justin Timberlake]] and [[Gabe Witcher]] for the soundtrack to the [[Coen Brothers]]' 2013 film ''[[Inside Llewyn Davis]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/11/03/242103173/first-listen-soundtrack-inside-llewyn-davis |title=First Listen: Soundtrack, 'Inside Llewyn Davis' |publisher=NPR |date=2013-11-03 |accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>\n* [[Ryan Boldt]] on his 2014 album ''Broadside Ballads''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ryan Boldt \u2013 Broadside Ballads|url = http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2015/09/ryan-boldt-broadside-ballads/|website = Folk Radio UK|access-date = 2016-05-16|language = en-US}}</ref>\n* [[The Mahones]] on their 2014 album ''[[The Hunger & The Fight]]''\n* [[Blackthorn]] on their album ''[[Nil na La]]''\n* [[Glen Hansard]], lead singer of [[The Frames]], and [[Damien Dempsey]], to raise funds for the charity [[Society of Saint Vincent de Paul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2010.theframes.ie/|title=The Frames|publisher=2010.theframes.ie|accessdate=2013-11-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110204539/http://2010.theframes.ie/|archivedate=10 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n==Notable performances==\n\n[[Doug Anthony All Stars|The Doug Anthony Allstars]] performed a medley (a variation on Fred Geis\u2019s \"Lament for Brendan Behan\" prefacing \"The Auld Triangle\") on the Australian ABC program The Big Gig in the late 1980s.<ref>{{Citation|last=hismerrymen|title=DAAS: The Big Gig - The Auld Triangle / Brendan Behan Is Dead|date=2010-03-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dRAOK97sDXg|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref>\n\n[[The Frames]] performed it as the final song of a two-hour concert at the Vic Theater in Chicago on 23 November 2010. They performed the song live on [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] television's ''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'' on 18 December of the same year.\nU2 played a live cover version at Croke Park, Dublin on 24 July 2009 as part of the 360 tour. [[Bono]] joined lead singer [[Glen Hansard]] on 8 May 2012 in New York City's [[The Living Room]] venue to perform the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vimeo.com/41819199 |title=Glen Hansard w/ Bono \"The Auld Triangle\" on Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo.com |date=2012-05-08 |accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>\n\nAt the Ceiliuradh (celebration) at [[Royal Albert Hall]] on 10 April 2014, it was sung by a collection of performers including [[Glen Hansard]], [[Lisa Hannigan]], [[Elvis Costello]], Conor O\u2019Brien (of [[Villagers (band)|Villagers]]), [[Paul Brady]], [[Imelda May]], [[John Sheahan]], [[D\u00f3nal Lunny]], [[Andy Irvine (musician)|Andy Irvine]] and [[The Gloaming (group)|The Gloaming]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.allmusic.com/search/songs/The+Auld+Triangle song search for \"The Auld Triangle\"] at [[Allmusic|allmusic.com]].\n*{{MusicBrainz work|title=The Auld Triangle|id=87548752-ae76-47d3-8f29-aca8aedda08b}}\n\n{{The Dubliners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Auld Triangle, The}}\n[[Category:1954 songs]]\n[[Category:Irish songs]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:The Dubliners songs]]\n[[Category:The Pogues songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about prison]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=January 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2008}}\n\"'''The Auld Triangle'''\" is a song, which was first performed publicly as a part of the play ''[[The Quare Fellow]]'' (1954) by [[Brendan Behan]].  Brendan credited his brother [[Dominic Behan]] for writing it. 2 years later, Dominic released it on an album called Irish Songs. \nThe song was later made famous by [[Luke Kelly]], [[Ronnie Drew]] and [[The Dubliners]] in the late 1960s, and was revived for a new audience by Irish rock band the Pogues on their 1984 album ''Red Roses for Me''.\n\n==Content==\nThe song is used to introduce the play, a story about the occurrences in a prison (in real life [[Mountjoy Prison]] where Behan had once been lodged) the day a convict is set to be executed. The triangle in the title refers to the large metal triangle which was beaten daily in Mountjoy Prison to waken the inmates (\"The Auld Triangle goes Jingle Jangle\"). The triangle still hangs in the prison at the centre where the wings meet on a metal gate. It is no longer used, though the hammer to beat it is mounted beside it.\nIn the original play by Brendan Behan, the song is written as the \"old triangle\" not \"auld triangle\". \n\nThe triangle was rung regularly to signify points in the prison's routine.\n[[File:Mountjoy Jail and Prison Van.jpg|thumb|right|The Quare Fellow takes place in Mountjoy prison during the early 1950's]]\nA second level of meaning is hinted at in the final verse in which the singer imagines himself dwelling in the women's prison. Another mourns the separation from \"his girl Sal\". These hint at the internal erotic fantasies that prisoners  use to separate themselves from the harsh prison environment. In this meaning  the old triangle becomes the female pudenda and the Royal Canal the vagina. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://songoftheisles.com/tag/the-auld-triangle/|title=The Auld Triangle|last=|first=|date=|website={{!}} Song of the Isles|language=en|access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAs with many Irish ballads, the lyrics have been changed with each passing cover.  For example, the [[Dropkick Murphys]] recording condenses the structure into a three-lyric section song with a chorus based on the last two lines of each stanza in the original.\n\n== Chorus ==\n<blockquote>''And the auld triangle went jingle-jangle''</blockquote><blockquote>''All along the banks of the Royal Canal''</blockquote>\n\n==Notable recordings==\nThis song has been recorded by:\n* [[The Clancy Brothers & Tommy Makem]] on ''[[Ain't It Grand Boys]]'' (recorded 1964, released 1995, as \"Royal Canal\") and ''The Bold Fenian Men'' (1969, as \"The Old Triangle\")\n* [[Liam Clancy]] as \"Royal Canal\" on his self-titled 1965 album (reissued with additional tracks in 1999 as ''Irish Troubadour'')\n* [[Ian & Sylvia]] as \"The Royal Canal\" for their ''Four Strong Winds'' album in 1963\n* [[The Dubliners]], on several albums, notably the 1967 album ''[[More of the Hard Stuff]]''\n* [[The Pogues]] on the 1984 album ''[[Red Roses for Me]]''\n* [[Dropkick Murphys]] on the 2005 album ''[[The Warrior's Code]]''. Their version was also included on the compilation ''Vans Off the Wall Volume VII''.\n* [[The High Kings]] on ''The High Kings'' (2008)\n* [[Bob Dylan]] and [[The Band]] also recorded a rendition of the song during their [[List of Basement Tapes songs|Basement Tapes sessions]] in 1967.  This recording is available on bootleg recordings but does not appear on the official ''[[The Basement Tapes]]'' album released in 1975. It finally appeared in 2014 on the official release, ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 11: The Basement Tapes Complete]]''. \n* [[Lifvens V\u00e4nner]] Swedish band recorded this song for their album \"Lifvs Levenes\", released 1997.\n* [[Bert Jansch]] for his 2006 album ''[[The Black Swan (Bert Jansch album)|The Black Swan]]''\n* [[Jeff Tweedy]] on his tour DVD ''[[Sunken Treasure: Live in the Pacific Northwest]]''\n* [[Oysterband|The Oysterband]] for their now-deleted 'Alive and Acoustic' recording\n* [[Glen Hansard]], lead singer of [[The Frames]], and [[Damien Dempsey]], to raise funds for the charity [[Society of Saint Vincent de Paul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2010.theframes.ie/|title=The Frames|publisher=2010.theframes.ie|accessdate=2013-11-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110204539/http://2010.theframes.ie/|archivedate=10 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n* [[Patrick Clifford (musician)|Patrick Clifford]], on ''[[Chance of a Start]]''\n* [[Blackthorn]] on their album ''[[Nil na La]]''\n* [[Cat Power]] for her 2008 EP ''[[Dark End of the Street (EP)|Dark End of the Street]]''\n* [[Chris Thile]], [[Chris Eldridge]], [[Marcus Mumford]], [[Justin Timberlake]] and [[Gabe Witcher]] for the soundtrack to the [[Coen Brothers]]' 2013 film ''[[Inside Llewyn Davis]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/11/03/242103173/first-listen-soundtrack-inside-llewyn-davis |title=First Listen: Soundtrack, 'Inside Llewyn Davis' |publisher=NPR |date=2013-11-03 |accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>\n* [[The Mahones]] on their 2014 album ''[[The Hunger & The Fight]]''\n* [[Ryan Boldt]] on his 2014 album ''Broadside Ballads''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ryan Boldt \u2013 Broadside Ballads|url = http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2015/09/ryan-boldt-broadside-ballads/|website = Folk Radio UK|access-date = 2016-05-16|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Notable performances==\n\n[[Doug Anthony All Stars|The Doug Anthony Allstars]] performed a medley (a variation on Fred Geis\u2019s \"Lament for Brendan Behan\" prefacing \"The Auld Triangle\") on the Australian ABC program The Big Gig in the late 1980s.<ref>{{Citation|last=hismerrymen|title=DAAS: The Big Gig - The Auld Triangle / Brendan Behan Is Dead|date=2010-03-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dRAOK97sDXg|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref>\n\n[[The Frames]] performed it as the final song of a two-hour concert at the Vic Theater in Chicago on 23 November 2010. They performed the song live on [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] television's ''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'' on 18 December of the same year.\nU2 played a live cover version at Croke Park, Dublin on 24 July 2009 as part of the 360 tour. [[Bono]] joined lead singer [[Glen Hansard]] on 8 May 2012 in New York City's [[The Living Room]] venue to perform the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vimeo.com/41819199 |title=Glen Hansard w/ Bono \"The Auld Triangle\" on Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo.com |date=2012-05-08 |accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>\n\nAt the Ceiliuradh (celebration) at [[Royal Albert Hall]] on 10 April 2014, it was sung by a collection of performers including [[Glen Hansard]], [[Lisa Hannigan]], [[Elvis Costello]], Conor O\u2019Brien (of [[Villagers (band)|Villagers]]), [[Paul Brady]], [[Imelda May]], [[John Sheahan]], [[D\u00f3nal Lunny]], [[Andy Irvine (musician)|Andy Irvine]] and [[The Gloaming (group)|The Gloaming]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.allmusic.com/search/songs/The+Auld+Triangle song search for \"The Auld Triangle\"] at [[Allmusic|allmusic.com]].\n*{{MusicBrainz work|title=The Auld Triangle|id=87548752-ae76-47d3-8f29-aca8aedda08b}}\n\n{{The Dubliners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Auld Triangle, The}}\n[[Category:1954 songs]]\n[[Category:Irish songs]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:The Dubliners songs]]\n[[Category:The Pogues songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about prison]]\n", "name_user": "Brunswicknic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Recording in chrono order (who influence who?)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Auld_Triangle"}
{"title_page": "DXTS", "text_new": "{{short description|Radio station in the Philippines}}\n{{Infobox Radio station \n | name = DXTS (DZRH News FM)\n | image =\n | city = [[General Santos]]\n | area = [[South Cotabato]], [[Sultan Kudarat]], [[Sarangani]], parts of [[Cotabato|North Cotabato]], [[Maguindanao Province]], [[Bukidnon]], [[Davao Occidental]] and [[Davao del Sur]]\n | branding = 94.3 DZRH News FM\n | slogan = \n | airdate = January 1, 1999 (as Hot FM)<br>July 1, 2009 (as Easy Rock)<br>February 24, 2014 (as Yes FM)<br>May 1, 2017 (as Yes The Best)<br>September 2019 (as DZRH News FM)\n | frequency = 94.3 MHz\n | format = [[Soft Adult Contemporary]], [[News radio|News]], [[Talk radio|Talk]]\n | power = 20,000 [[watt]]s\n | erp = 93,000 [[watt]]s\n | class = \n | callsign_meaning = Brodca '''S''' '''T'''ing (Reversing from the callsign/derived from the name of [[Manila Broadcasting Company]]) and/or '''S'''an'''T'''os (derived from [[General Santos City]])\n | owner = [[Manila Broadcasting Company]]\n | licensee = Cebu Broadcasting Company\n | webcast = [https://www.radionomy.com/en/radio/dzrhnews-fmgeneralsantos/index/ Listen Live]\n | website = [http://dzrhnews.com.ph www.dzrhnews.com.ph]\n | sister_stations = [[DXGH|DZRH General Santos]], [[DXWK|101.5 Love Radio]]\n}}\n\n'''DXTS''' (94.3 FM), broadcasting as '''94.3 DZRH News FM''', is a commercial [[radio station]] owned by Cebu Broadcasting Company, an affiliate of [[Manila Broadcasting Company]]. The station's [[studio]] and transmitter are located at the 3rd floor, RD Plaza Bldg., Pendatun Ave., Brgy. Dadiangas West, [[General Santos City]]. It is operating 24 hours a day.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://storage.googleapis.com/request-attachments/AV4y9qh3QvqYRdiDILKyN9nVIEnGnFovM9uuKB8iRaRW7PRrO633PGaXjSEULkqvEmjorBtVejJ00OBQf6uq5cH0nMZNFTt12UrY/FM%20STATIONS_2019.pdf|title = 2019 NTC FM Stations|website = [[Freedom of Information Order (Philippines)|foi.gov.ph]]|access-date = 2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\nDespite carrying the DZRH brand, it usually airs its own programming. It is the second FM station of MBC to carry a hybrid of music & news after [[DYBG|Ben FM]] in [[Medellin, Cebu|Northern Cebu]].\n\n==History==\nIt was formerly known as '''Hot FM''' carrying a [[Middle of the road (music)|mass-based]] format from 1999 to May 2009. In July 2009, it changed its brand to '''Easy Rock''', with a [[Soft AC]] format, competing with [[DXQS|Home Radio]]. In February 2014, the station, along with MBC's O&O [[Hot FM (Philippine radio network)|Hot FM]] stations, rebranded as '''Yes FM''', reverting to its mass-based format. On May 1, 2017, it was rebranded again as '''Yes The Best'''. On September 2019, it was reformatted into a news/talk format, this time using the DZRH brand.\n\n==DZRH stations==\n{{Main|List of Manila Broadcasting Company stations}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Manila Broadcasting Company]] - Parent Company of Cebu Broadcasting Company.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{General Santos FM}}\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dxts}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in General Santos]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1999]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Radio station in the Philippines}}\n{{Infobox Radio station \n | name = DXTS (DZRH News FM)\n | image =\n | city = [[General Santos]]\n | area = [[South Cotabato]], [[Sultan Kudarat]], [[Sarangani]], parts of [[Cotabato|North Cotabato]], [[Maguindanao Province]], [[Bukidnon]], [[Davao Occidental]] and [[Davao del Sur]]\n | branding = 94.3 DZRH News FM\n | slogan = \n | airdate = January 1, 1999 (as Hot FM)<br>July 1, 2009 (as Easy Rock)<br>February 24, 2014 (as Yes FM)<br>May 1, 2017 (as Yes The Best)<br>September 2019 (as DZRH News FM)\n | frequency = 94.3 MHz\n | format = [[Middle of the road (music)|Contemporary MOR]], [[News radio|News]], [[Talk radio|Talk]]\n | power = 20,000 [[watt]]s\n | erp = 93,000 [[watt]]s\n | class = \n | callsign_meaning = Brodca '''S''' '''T'''ing (Reversing from the callsign/derived from the name of [[Manila Broadcasting Company]]) and/or '''S'''an'''T'''os (derived from [[General Santos City]])\n | owner = [[Manila Broadcasting Company]]\n | licensee = Cebu Broadcasting Company\n | webcast = [https://www.radionomy.com/en/radio/dzrhnews-fmgeneralsantos/index/ Listen Live]\n | website = [http://dzrhnews.com.ph www.dzrhnews.com.ph]\n | sister_stations = [[DXGH|DZRH General Santos]], [[DXWK|101.5 Love Radio]]\n}}\n\n'''DXTS''' (94.3 FM), broadcasting as '''94.3 DZRH News FM''', is a commercial [[radio station]] owned by Cebu Broadcasting Company, an affiliate of [[Manila Broadcasting Company]]. The station's [[studio]] and transmitter are located at the 3rd floor, RD Plaza Bldg., Pendatun Ave., Brgy. Dadiangas West, [[General Santos City]]. It is operating 24 hours a day.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://storage.googleapis.com/request-attachments/AV4y9qh3QvqYRdiDILKyN9nVIEnGnFovM9uuKB8iRaRW7PRrO633PGaXjSEULkqvEmjorBtVejJ00OBQf6uq5cH0nMZNFTt12UrY/FM%20STATIONS_2019.pdf|title = 2019 NTC FM Stations|website = [[Freedom of Information Order (Philippines)|foi.gov.ph]]|access-date = 2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\nDespite carrying the DZRH brand, it usually airs its own programming. It is the second FM station of MBC to carry a hybrid of music & news after [[DYBG|Ben FM]] in [[Medellin, Cebu|Northern Cebu]].\n\n==History==\nIt was formerly known as '''Hot FM''' carrying a [[Middle of the road (music)|mass-based]] format from 1999 to May 2009. In July 2009, it changed its brand to '''Easy Rock''', with a [[Soft AC]] format, competing with [[DXQS|Home Radio]]. In February 2014, the station, along with MBC's O&O [[Hot FM (Philippine radio network)|Hot FM]] stations, rebranded as '''Yes FM''', reverting to its mass-based format. On May 1, 2017, it was rebranded again as '''Yes The Best'''. On September 2019, it was reformatted into a news/talk format, this time using the DZRH brand.\n\n==DZRH stations==\n{{Main|List of Manila Broadcasting Company stations}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Manila Broadcasting Company]] - Parent Company of Cebu Broadcasting Company.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{General Santos FM}}\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dxts}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in General Santos]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1999]]\n", "name_user": "58.69.164.78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DXTS"}
{"title_page": "24 Oras", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|24 Horas}}\n{{short description|Philippine television show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = 24 Oras\n| image = 24 Oras title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card since 2019\n| genre = [[Newscast]]\n| company = [[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n| director = {{plain list|\n* Joel San Luis\n* Lirio Dayao {{small|(Weekends)}}}}\n| presenter = {{plain list|\n* [[Mel Tiangco]]\n* [[Mike Enriquez]]\n* [[Vicky Morales]]\n* '''Weekends'''\n* [[Pia Arcangel]]\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]]}}\n| narrated = {{plainlist|\n* Joel Reyes Zobel {{small|(2004\u20132014)}}\n* Mike Enriquez {{small|(since 2014)}}}}\n| theme_music_composer = Jimmy Antiporda\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| executive_producer = {{plain list|\n* Antonio Magsumbol \n* Nielsen Ocampo {{small|(Weekends)}}}}\n| location = [[GMA Network Center]], [[Quezon City]], Philippines (Studio 2: {{small|2004\u20132011, 2018\u20132019}}; Studio 5: {{small|2011\u20132018, since 2019}})\n| runtime = {{plain list|\n* 75-90 minutes\n* 30-45 minutes {{small|(Weekends)}}}}\n| network = [[GMA Network]] {{small|(simulcast on [[GMA News TV]])}}}}\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|2004|3|15}}\n| last_aired = present\n| website = http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/shows/24oras\n}}\n\n'''''24 Oras''''' (pronounced as Bente Kwatro Oras / {{translation|24 Hours}}) is a [[Philippine television]] newscast show broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. Anchored by [[Mel Tiangco]], [[Mike Enriquez]] and [[Vicky Morales]]. It premiered on March 15, 2004 replacing ''[[Frontpage: Ulat ni Mel Tiangco]]'' and worldwide on [[GMA Pinoy TV]]. The show is currently the network's flagship national network newscast, and simultaneously broadcasting on radio through [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB 594]] in [[Mega Manila]] and its [[List of GMA Network radio stations#Super Radyo AM stations|regional Super Radyo stations]] nationwide ([[DYSP|Super Radyo DYSP 909 Palawan]], [[DYSI|Super Radyo DYSI 1323 Iloilo]], [[DYSS|Super Radyo DYSS 999 Cebu]] and [[DXGM-AM|Super Radyo DXGM 1125 Davao]]).\n\n==Overview==\n===2004\u20132014: The early years===\n[[File:24 Oras studio.jpg|thumb|left|250px|''24 Oras'' set on February 21, 2011]]\n''24 Oras'' with its tagline, \"Dahil Hindi Natutulog ang Balita\" (translates as \"Because News Doesn't Sleep) premiered on March 15, 2004 at 6:15 pm and it was first broadcast from the Studio 2 of [[GMA Network Center]], replacing ''[[Frontpage: Ulat ni Mel Tiangco]]''. Frontpage anchor Mel Tiangco was joined by former ''[[Saksi]]'' anchor Mike Enriquez. Its first headline featured the [[2004 Philippine presidential election|2004 Philippine elections]], followed by a one-on-one live interview with Senator [[Panfilo Lacson]] discussing on Actor [[Fernando Poe Jr.]] proposed tandem meeting. Also in the telecast, TV host [[Pia Guanio]] was introduced as the new host for Showbiz Time, later renamed Chika Minute.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eFONogODqGg 24 Oras pilot episode (camrecorded)</ref> Weekend editions were aired when it deemed necessary. The show later moved its timeslot to 6:30 pm, and was extended to 90 minutes, also the following year, the newscast began airing internationally through [[GMA Pinoy TV]].\n\nOn December 1, 2005, the coverage by ''24 Oras'' of a siege of Camp Bagong Diwa was mentioned in the best news program category in the [[Asian Television Awards]] in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.onscreenasia.com/asiantvawards/ata2007/ata2005winners.html |title=Asian Television Awards 2005 Winners |access-date=January 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325155818/http://www.onscreenasia.com/asiantvawards/ata2007/ata2005winners.html |archive-date=March 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2008, the show was relaunched again with a multi-million peso studio set using LED, a new desk which is identical to the desk used by [[CBS Evening News]], new graphics, new titles, and its new tagline \"Tahanan ng Katotohanan\", while the \"Dahil Hindi Natutulog ang Balita\" tagline was dropped, but it was still used in the closing remarks.\n\nIn April 2010, the show became the home of Vizrt Touchscreen system a real-time broadcast solutions system which is used in the YouScoop segment designed and developed by GMA New Media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/2376/gma-7s-24-oras-and-saksi-unveil-new-sets-tonight-august-11|title=GMA-7\u2019s \"24 Oras\" and \"Saksi\" unveil new sets tonight, August 11|last=Dimaculangan|first=Jocelyn|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n\n''24 Oras'' became instrumental and controversial on covering the [[Manila hostage crisis]], the authorities ordered a media blackout, but failed, when covering live the arrest of the brother of the hostage-taker, the hostage-taker was apparently monitoring GMA-7 and found out about it; the situation became worse when gunshots were heard inside the bus assuming that the hostage taker was watching, it monitored the SWAT's movement of the rescue, the massacre ended at least one hour, when the hostage taker was shot dead on live TV, due to teargas that choked the bus.<ref>[https://pinoychannel.sa.com/category/24-oras/ http://www.cmfr-phil.org/2010/10/15/the-aug-23-hostage-taking-media-lapses-invited-government-intervention/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822012950/https://pinoychannel.sa.com/category/24-oras/ |date=August 22, 2017 }} Center for Media Freedom and Responsibility's review on the media's role of the November 20, 2013 incident</ref> The coverage ate up its primetime block, from 6:30-9:30pm, giving 19.7% of its audience share from AGB Nielsen.\n\nOn December 6, 2010, the news program updated its graphics. A day later, it updated its OBB and title card. On February 21, 2011, along with ''[[Unang Hirit]]'', ''[[Saksi]]'', and ''[[GMA Flash Report]]'', the newscast transferred its new studios, Studio 5; launched new graphics, new theme, and new OBB. The new theme music is a remix of 24 Oras 2008\u20132011 theme music and an element of an opera voice, originally used as a promo plug in 2010.\n\nOn October 10, 2011, ''24 Oras'' updated only its graphics. This also use a new font [[Antique Olive]] on their graphics, replacing [[Myriad (typeface)|Myriad]] font, which is used on other GMA newscasts.\n\nOn June 4, 2012, ''24 Oras'' launched its new weather segment titled I.M. Ready: GMA Weather (based on the advisory advertisement of the said title, and the branding of I.M. Ready). In June 2013, ''24 Oras'' introduced its augmented reality graphics, initially used at the beginning of the show for presentation/demonstration purposes. It is currently used for US Dollar exchange rate, Metro Manila air index (but removed in 2016), some live crosses and for other occasional purposes (such as Christmas/New Year Countdowns and demographics/data gathering in connection of a certain news story).\n\nA notable coverage of GMA News for \"Super Typhoon Yolanda\", covering the devastating Typhoon Haiyan (international name), won its 4th George Foster's Peabody Awards in 2014.\n\n===2014\u2013present: Enriquez, Tiangco, and Morales===\n[[File:P 20161121 160036 p.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|358x358px|A billboard showcasing the new logo of 24 Oras as seen from the [[GMA Network Center]].]]\n\nOn November 10, 2014, [[Vicky Morales]] joined ''24 Oras'' team as its third anchor. Also, GMA Regional newscasts for [[GMA Bicol|Bicol]], [[GMA Cebu|Cebu]], [[GMA Davao|Davao]], [[GMA Northern Mindanao|Northern Mindanao]], [[GMA Iloilo|Iloilo]],  [[GMA Dagupan|Dagupan]] and [[GMA Ilocos|Ilocos]] adopted the ''24 Oras'' branding.<ref>http://www.medianewser.com/2014/11/the-gma-news-anchor-shakeup-vicky.html The GMA News Anchor Shakeup</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/387200/cbb/gma-news-and-public-affairs-announces-big-changes-in-news-lineup/|title=GMA News and Public Affairs announces big changes in news lineup|website=GMA News Online}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2015, with GMA Network's plans of streamlining regional operations, [[24 Oras Ilokano|Ilokano]], [[24 Oras Bikol|Bikol]] and [[24 Oras Northern Mindanao|Northern Mindanao]] canceled, followed by the [[Ratsada 24 Oras|Iloilo]] edition on November 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/740106/gma-7-scraps-iloilo-city-news-program-lays-off-20-staff|title=GMA 7 scraps Iloilo City news program, lays off 20 staff|first=Nestor P. Burgos|last=Jr|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net}}</ref> On February 1, 2016, North Central Luzon (''24 Oras Amianan'') and Central Visayas editions of the newscast reverted to their respective titles: ''[[Balitang Amianan]]'' and ''[[Balitang Bisdak]]'', respectively. With the said downgrade, the Southern Mindanao edition (rebranded since October 3, 2016 as ''24 Oras Davao'') became the only regional edition of the newscast across the entire network. In addition, GMA also axed its remaining local non-news programs for its regional viewers.\n\nAfter 11 years of delivering showbiz news on Chika Minute, [[Pia Guanio]] bid farewell to ''24 Oras'' to concentrate on her family life. She is currently on the networks' noontime variety show, [[Eat Bulaga!]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/495002/full-statement-gma-network-on-pia-guanio-s-departure-from-24-oras/story/|title=FULL STATEMENT: GMA Network on Pia Guanio\u2019s departure from 24 Oras|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/16064/pia-guanio-leaves-chika-minute-after-eleven-years/story|title=Pia Guanio leaves Chika Minute after eleven years|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/494990/pia-guanio-leaving-24-oras-showbiz-segment/story/|title=Pia Guanio leaving 24 Oras showbiz segment|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Iya Villania]] took over as the new Chika Minute anchor on June 15, 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/502314/iya-villania-is-new-24-oras-chika-minute-host/story/|title=Iya Villania is new 24 Oras \u2018Chika Minute\u2019 host|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/16544/gma-news-announces-iya-villania-as-new-chika-minute-host/story|title=GMA News announces Iya Villania as new Chika Minute host|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2018, former ''Atomic Sports'' segment host [[Atom Araullo]] joined the newscast as substitute anchor for Mike Enriquez, who went on medical leave for his kidney treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/28387/atom-araullo-to-pinch-hit-for-mike-enriquez-in-24-oras|title=Atom Araullo to pinch-hit for Mike Enriquez in 24 Oras|website=PEP.ph}}</ref><ref>[https://www.lionheartv.net/2018/08/on-medical-leave-mike-enriquez-explains-absence-in-gma-network-dzbb-programs ON MEDICAL LEAVE: Mike Enriquez explains absence in GMA Network, DZBB Programs]/</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/665399/24-oras-welcomes-back-atom-araullo/story/|title=WATCH: 24 Oras welcomes back Atom Araullo|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://showbizchika.net/atom-araullo-temporarily-replaces-mike-enriquez-in-24-oras/|title=Atom Araullo temporarily replaces Mike Enriquez in 24 Oras|work=ShowBiz Chika|access-date=2018-10-02|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=GMA News|title=Welcome back, Atom!|date=2018-08-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=soVG1MmVtcI|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> Enriquez returned to the newscast on November 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/46079/look-mike-enriquez-returns-to-24-oras/story|title=LOOK: Mike Enriquez returns to 24 Oras|last=Soriano|first=Gia Allana|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2018, the newscast began airing on its original set Studio 2, Studio 5 (which was also used by its weekend edition and ''[[Saksi]]'' as well as ''[[State of the Nation with Jessica Soho]]'') underwent a major overhaul to become the main studio for the Eleksyon 2019 special coverage. Studio 2 is also the studio where [[GMA News TV]]'s programs are filmed.\n\nOn May 13, 2019, in time with the [[2019 Philippine general election]], the newscast returned to the newly-renovated P63 million peso state of the art Studio 5 constructed by U.S. based company FX Design Group, along with ''[[Saksi]]'' and ''[[State of the Nation with Jessica Soho]]''. The newscast aired with reformatted graphics, lower thirds(now using the [[Avenir (typeface)|Avenir]]), logo and a new OBB was introduced the following night while retaining its theme music used since 2016. The brand new set also uses computer-generated graphics provided by Vizrt, integrate within the set in real time, creating a [[virtual studio]]. It currently uses alongside [[Augmented Reality]] graphics, for \"''Sumbungan Ng Bayan''\" and \"''Kapusong Totoo''\" segments, it also use for Christmas/New Year countdowns, or other related topic to emphasize data gathering and issue explanation.\n\n==Weekend edition==\nOn February 21, 2010, the weekend edition of the show was launched, replacing ''[[GMA Weekend Report]]'', and originally anchored by [[Pia Arcangel]] and [[Jiggy Manicad]].<ref>{{cite news|title=24 Oras Weekend premieres this Sunday, February 21|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/5612/24-oras-weekend-premieres-this-sunday-february-21|accessdate=April 26, 2018|work=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=February 20, 2012}}</ref> On April 21, 2018, Manicad left the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/04/22/1808377/jiggy-manicad-leaves-media-next-level-public-service|title=Jiggy Manicad leaves media for \u2018next level\u2019 of public service {{!}} Philstar.com|website=philstar.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/pepalerts/cabinet-files/21675/jiggy-manicad-magpapaalamna-sa-mga-programa-niya-sa-gma-news|title=Jiggy Manicad, nagpaalam na sa mga programa niya sa GMA News|last=PEP.ph|date=2018-04-20|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2018/04/watch-jiggy-manicad-announces-his-departure-from-the-media-industry.html|title=Watch: Jiggy Manicad announces his departure from the media industry|website=www.medianewser.com|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref><ref>http://www.medianewser.com/2018/10/jiggy-manicad-makes-senatorial-bid-official.html?m=1</ref> In August 2018, [[Ivan Mayrina]] became co-anchor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/43076/ivan-mayrina-co-anchors-24-oras-weekend/story|title=Ivan Mayrina co-anchors '24 Oras Weekend'|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2018/08/ivan-mayrina-officially-the-new-co-anchor-of-24-oras-weekend.html?m=1|title=Ivan Mayrina officially the new co-anchor of '24 Oras Weekend'|website=www.medianewser.com|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref>\n\n==Regional newscasts==\nOn January 29, 2016, GMA Regional TV announced the return of ''Balitang Amianan'' and ''Balitang Bisdak'' on February 1, 2016 as a pre-programming and later preemption of the first 30 minutes of [[Wowowin]], after more than a year of using 24 Oras brand. As a result, ''24 Oras Southern Mindanao'' remained to its branding since November 10, 2014 (rebranded to ''24 Oras Davao'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/GMARegionalTV/posts/1014497441949224|title=GMA Regional TV|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, 2017, the Davao edition adopted the graphics, OBB, and soundtrack of the national edition; while the two other regional newscasts changed only the graphics and OBB similarly to the said national newscast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m_-RL1Crg0o|title=24 Oras Davao OBB (January 2, 2017-present)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZIpUI6SdPNA|title=Balitang Amianan OBB (January 2, 2017-present)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nOn August 25, 2017, ''24 Oras Davao'' ended its more than 2-year run to pave way for [[Mindanao]]-wide newscast, [[One Mindanao]].\n\n===Previous regional versions===\n*''[[24 Oras Ilokano]]'' (GMA Ilocos) <small>(replaced by [[Balitang Amianan]])</small>\n*''24 Oras North Central Luzon/24 Oras Amianan'' (GMA Dagupan) <small>(reverted to [[Balitang Amianan]])</small>\n*''[[24 Oras Bikol]]'' (GMA Bicol) \n*''24 Oras Western Visayas/[[Ratsada 24 Oras]]'' (GMA Iloilo) <small>(replaced by [[One Western Visayas]])</small>\n*''24 Oras Central Visayas'' (GMA Cebu) <small>(reverted to [[Balitang Bisdak]])</small>\n*''[[24 Oras Northern Mindanao]]'' (GMA Northern Mindanao) <small>(replaced by [[One Mindanao]])</small>\n*''24 Oras Southern Mindanao''/''24 Oras Davao'' (GMA Davao) <small>(replaced by [[One Mindanao]])</small>\n\n==Anchors==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Mike Enriquez in White Plains, Quezon City.jpg\n|caption1 = Mike Enriquez serves as an anchor.\n|width1 = 150\n}}\n\n* [[Mel Tiangco]] {{small|(since 2004)}}\n* [[Mike Enriquez]] {{small|(since 2004)}}\n* [[Vicky Morales]] {{small|(since 2014)}}\n\n;Weekend anchors\n* [[Pia Arcangel]] {{small|(since 2010; interim anchor for Tiangco and Soho)}}\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]] {{small|(since 2018)}}\n\n;Segment anchors\n* Nathaniel \"Mang Tani\" Cruz {{small|(since 2012; ''IM Ready: GMA Weather'' anchor)}}\n* [[Iya Villania]] {{small|(since 2015; for ''Chika Minute'' segme