ce-entertainment-awards \"44th Guillermo Mendoza Box-Office Entertainment Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403190603/http://www.pep.ph/photos/3796/44th-guillermo-mendoza-box-office-entertainment-awards |date=April 3, 2019 }}. ''Pep.ph''. Retrieved 2014-05-19.</ref>\n\n:'''Northwest Samar State University Annual Awards'''\n* 2013 Winner, Best News and Public Affairs Program\n* 2013 Winner, Mike Enriquez: Best News and Public Affairs Male Program Anchor\n* 2013 Winner, Mel Tiangco: Best News and Public Affairs Female Program Anchor\n* 2012 Winner, Best News and Public Affairs Program\n* 2012 Winner, Mike Enriquez: Best News and Public Affairs Male Program Anchor\n\n:'''PMAP Makatao Awards for Media Excellence'''\n* 2012 Winner, Best News Program\n* 2012 Winner, Mel Tiangco: Best TV Female Newscaster\n\n:'''National Academy of Television Arts & Science (Emmy Awards)'''\n* 2013 Winner, Best Documentary\n\n:'''George Foster Peabody Awards'''\n* 2014 Winner, Best News Coverage for \"Super Typhoon Yolanda\"; along with State of the Nation, Saksi, 24 Oras Weekend, & Kapuso Mo, Jessica Soho\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/shows/24oras}}\n* {{IMDb title|0764672}}\n\n{{24 Oras}}\n{{PhilNetworkEveningNewsShows}}\n{{PhilNetworkHourlyNewsBulletins}}\n{{GMA Network (current and upcoming original programming)}}\n{{GMA News and Public Affairs}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network news programs]]\n[[Category:GMA News and Public Affairs programs]]\n[[Category:Philippine television news programs]]\n[[Category:2004 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s Philippine television series]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Flagship evening news programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|24 Horas}}\n{{short description|Philippine television show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = 24 Oras\n| image = 24 Oras title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card since 2019\n| genre = [[Newscast]]\n| company = [[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n| director = {{plain list|\n* Joel San Luis\n* Lirio Dayao {{small|(Weekends)}}}}\n| presenter = {{plain list|\n* [[Mel Tiangco]]\n* [[Mike Enriquez]]\n* [[Vicky Morales]]\n* '''Weekends'''\n* [[Pia Arcangel]]\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]]}}\n| narrated = {{plainlist|\n* Joel Reyes Zobel {{small|(2004\u20132014)}}\n* Mike Enriquez {{small|(since 2014)}}}}\n| theme_music_composer = Jimmy Antiporda\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| executive_producer = {{plain list|\n* Antonio Magsumbol \n* Nielsen Ocampo {{small|(Weekends)}}}}\n| location = [[GMA Network Center]], [[Quezon City]], Philippines (Studio 2: {{small|2004\u20132011, 2018\u20132019}}; Studio 5: {{small|2011\u20132018, since 2019}})\n| runtime = {{plain list|\n* 75-90 minutes\n* 30-45 minutes {{small|(Weekends)}}}}\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|2004|3|15}}\n| last_aired = present\n| website = http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/shows/24oras\n}}\n\n'''''24 Oras''''' (pronounced as Bente Kwatro Oras / {{translation|24 Hours}}) is a [[Philippine television]] newscast show broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. Anchored by [[Mel Tiangco]], [[Mike Enriquez]] and [[Vicky Morales]]. It premiered on March 15, 2004 replacing ''[[Frontpage: Ulat ni Mel Tiangco]]'' and worldwide on [[GMA Pinoy TV]]. The show is currently the network's flagship national network newscast, and simultaneously broadcasting on radio through [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB 594]] in [[Mega Manila]] and its [[List of GMA Network radio stations#Super Radyo AM stations|regional Super Radyo stations]] nationwide ([[DYSP|Super Radyo DYSP 909 Palawan]], [[DYSI|Super Radyo DYSI 1323 Iloilo]], [[DYSS|Super Radyo DYSS 999 Cebu]] and [[DXGM-AM|Super Radyo DXGM 1125 Davao]]).\n\n==Overview==\n===2004\u20132014: The early years===\n[[File:24 Oras studio.jpg|thumb|left|250px|''24 Oras'' set on February 21, 2011]]\n''24 Oras'' with its tagline, \"Dahil Hindi Natutulog ang Balita\" (translates as \"Because News Doesn't Sleep) premiered on March 15, 2004 at 6:15 pm and it was first broadcast from the Studio 2 of [[GMA Network Center]], replacing ''[[Frontpage: Ulat ni Mel Tiangco]]''. Frontpage anchor Mel Tiangco was joined by former ''[[Saksi]]'' anchor Mike Enriquez. Its first headline featured the [[2004 Philippine presidential election|2004 Philippine elections]], followed by a one-on-one live interview with Senator [[Panfilo Lacson]] discussing on Actor [[Fernando Poe Jr.]] proposed tandem meeting. Also in the telecast, TV host [[Pia Guanio]] was introduced as the new host for Showbiz Time, later renamed Chika Minute.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eFONogODqGg 24 Oras pilot episode (camrecorded)</ref> Weekend editions were aired when it deemed necessary. The show later moved its timeslot to 6:30 pm, and was extended to 90 minutes, also the following year, the newscast began airing internationally through [[GMA Pinoy TV]].\n\nOn December 1, 2005, the coverage by ''24 Oras'' of a siege of Camp Bagong Diwa was mentioned in the best news program category in the [[Asian Television Awards]] in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.onscreenasia.com/asiantvawards/ata2007/ata2005winners.html |title=Asian Television Awards 2005 Winners |access-date=January 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325155818/http://www.onscreenasia.com/asiantvawards/ata2007/ata2005winners.html |archive-date=March 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2008, the show was relaunched again with a multi-million peso studio set using LED, a new desk which is identical to the desk used by [[CBS Evening News]], new graphics, new titles, and its new tagline \"Tahanan ng Katotohanan\", while the \"Dahil Hindi Natutulog ang Balita\" tagline was dropped, but it was still used in the closing remarks.\n\nIn April 2010, the show became the home of Vizrt Touchscreen system a real-time broadcast solutions system which is used in the YouScoop segment designed and developed by GMA New Media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/2376/gma-7s-24-oras-and-saksi-unveil-new-sets-tonight-august-11|title=GMA-7\u2019s \"24 Oras\" and \"Saksi\" unveil new sets tonight, August 11|last=Dimaculangan|first=Jocelyn|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n\n''24 Oras'' became instrumental and controversial on covering the [[Manila hostage crisis]], the authorities ordered a media blackout, but failed, when covering live the arrest of the brother of the hostage-taker, the hostage-taker was apparently monitoring GMA-7 and found out about it; the situation became worse when gunshots were heard inside the bus assuming that the hostage taker was watching, it monitored the SWAT's movement of the rescue, the massacre ended at least one hour, when the hostage taker was shot dead on live TV, due to teargas that choked the bus.<ref>[https://pinoychannel.sa.com/category/24-oras/ http://www.cmfr-phil.org/2010/10/15/the-aug-23-hostage-taking-media-lapses-invited-government-intervention/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822012950/https://pinoychannel.sa.com/category/24-oras/ |date=August 22, 2017 }} Center for Media Freedom and Responsibility's review on the media's role of the November 20, 2013 incident</ref> The coverage ate up its primetime block, from 6:30-9:30pm, giving 19.7% of its audience share from AGB Nielsen.\n\nOn December 6, 2010, the news program updated its graphics. A day later, it updated its OBB and title card. On February 21, 2011, along with ''[[Unang Hirit]]'', ''[[Saksi]]'', and ''[[GMA Flash Report]]'', the newscast transferred its new studios, Studio 5; launched new graphics, new theme, and new OBB. The new theme music is a remix of 24 Oras 2008\u20132011 theme music and an element of an opera voice, originally used as a promo plug in 2010.\n\nOn October 10, 2011, ''24 Oras'' updated only its graphics. This also use a new font [[Antique Olive]] on their graphics, replacing [[Myriad (typeface)|Myriad]] font, which is used on other GMA newscasts.\n\nOn June 4, 2012, ''24 Oras'' launched its new weather segment titled I.M. Ready: GMA Weather (based on the advisory advertisement of the said title, and the branding of I.M. Ready). In June 2013, ''24 Oras'' introduced its augmented reality graphics, initially used at the beginning of the show for presentation/demonstration purposes. It is currently used for US Dollar exchange rate, Metro Manila air index (but removed in 2016), some live crosses and for other occasional purposes (such as Christmas/New Year Countdowns and demographics/data gathering in connection of a certain news story).\n\nA notable coverage of GMA News for \"Super Typhoon Yolanda\", covering the devastating Typhoon Haiyan (international name), won its 4th George Foster's Peabody Awards in 2014.\n\n===2014\u2013present: Enriquez, Tiangco, and Morales===\n[[File:P 20161121 160036 p.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|358x358px|A billboard showcasing the new logo of 24 Oras as seen from the [[GMA Network Center]].]]\n\nOn November 10, 2014, [[Vicky Morales]] joined ''24 Oras'' team as its third anchor. Also, GMA Regional newscasts for [[GMA Bicol|Bicol]], [[GMA Cebu|Cebu]], [[GMA Davao|Davao]], [[GMA Northern Mindanao|Northern Mindanao]], [[GMA Iloilo|Iloilo]],  [[GMA Dagupan|Dagupan]] and [[GMA Ilocos|Ilocos]] adopted the ''24 Oras'' branding.<ref>http://www.medianewser.com/2014/11/the-gma-news-anchor-shakeup-vicky.html The GMA News Anchor Shakeup</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/387200/cbb/gma-news-and-public-affairs-announces-big-changes-in-news-lineup/|title=GMA News and Public Affairs announces big changes in news lineup|website=GMA News Online}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2015, with GMA Network's plans of streamlining regional operations, [[24 Oras Ilokano|Ilokano]], [[24 Oras Bikol|Bikol]] and [[24 Oras Northern Mindanao|Northern Mindanao]] canceled, followed by the [[Ratsada 24 Oras|Iloilo]] edition on November 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/740106/gma-7-scraps-iloilo-city-news-program-lays-off-20-staff|title=GMA 7 scraps Iloilo City news program, lays off 20 staff|first=Nestor P. Burgos|last=Jr|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net}}</ref> On February 1, 2016, North Central Luzon (''24 Oras Amianan'') and Central Visayas editions of the newscast reverted to their respective titles: ''[[Balitang Amianan]]'' and ''[[Balitang Bisdak]]'', respectively. With the said downgrade, the Southern Mindanao edition (rebranded since October 3, 2016 as ''24 Oras Davao'') became the only regional edition of the newscast across the entire network. In addition, GMA also axed its remaining local non-news programs for its regional viewers.\n\nAfter 11 years of delivering showbiz news on Chika Minute, [[Pia Guanio]] bid farewell to ''24 Oras'' to concentrate on her family life. She is currently on the networks' noontime variety show, [[Eat Bulaga!]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/495002/full-statement-gma-network-on-pia-guanio-s-departure-from-24-oras/story/|title=FULL STATEMENT: GMA Network on Pia Guanio\u2019s departure from 24 Oras|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/16064/pia-guanio-leaves-chika-minute-after-eleven-years/story|title=Pia Guanio leaves Chika Minute after eleven years|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/494990/pia-guanio-leaving-24-oras-showbiz-segment/story/|title=Pia Guanio leaving 24 Oras showbiz segment|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Iya Villania]] took over as the new Chika Minute anchor on June 15, 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/502314/iya-villania-is-new-24-oras-chika-minute-host/story/|title=Iya Villania is new 24 Oras \u2018Chika Minute\u2019 host|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/16544/gma-news-announces-iya-villania-as-new-chika-minute-host/story|title=GMA News announces Iya Villania as new Chika Minute host|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2018, former ''Atomic Sports'' segment host [[Atom Araullo]] joined the newscast as substitute anchor for Mike Enriquez, who went on medical leave for his kidney treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/28387/atom-araullo-to-pinch-hit-for-mike-enriquez-in-24-oras|title=Atom Araullo to pinch-hit for Mike Enriquez in 24 Oras|website=PEP.ph}}</ref><ref>[https://www.lionheartv.net/2018/08/on-medical-leave-mike-enriquez-explains-absence-in-gma-network-dzbb-programs ON MEDICAL LEAVE: Mike Enriquez explains absence in GMA Network, DZBB Programs]/</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/665399/24-oras-welcomes-back-atom-araullo/story/|title=WATCH: 24 Oras welcomes back Atom Araullo|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://showbizchika.net/atom-araullo-temporarily-replaces-mike-enriquez-in-24-oras/|title=Atom Araullo temporarily replaces Mike Enriquez in 24 Oras|work=ShowBiz Chika|access-date=2018-10-02|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=GMA News|title=Welcome back, Atom!|date=2018-08-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=soVG1MmVtcI|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> Enriquez returned to the newscast on November 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/46079/look-mike-enriquez-returns-to-24-oras/story|title=LOOK: Mike Enriquez returns to 24 Oras|last=Soriano|first=Gia Allana|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2018, the newscast began airing on its original set Studio 2, Studio 5 (which was also used by its weekend edition and ''[[Saksi]]'' as well as ''[[State of the Nation with Jessica Soho]]'') underwent a major overhaul to become the main studio for the Eleksyon 2019 special coverage. Studio 2 is also the studio where [[GMA News TV]]'s programs are filmed.\n\nOn May 13, 2019, in time with the [[2019 Philippine general election]], the newscast returned to the newly-renovated P63 million peso state of the art Studio 5 constructed by U.S. based company FX Design Group, along with ''[[Saksi]]'' and ''[[State of the Nation with Jessica Soho]]''. The newscast aired with reformatted graphics, lower thirds(now using the [[Avenir (typeface)|Avenir]]), logo and a new OBB was introduced the following night while retaining its theme music used since 2016. The brand new set also uses computer-generated graphics provided by Vizrt, integrate within the set in real time, creating a [[virtual studio]]. It currently uses alongside [[Augmented Reality]] graphics, for \"''Sumbungan Ng Bayan''\" and \"''Kapusong Totoo''\" segments, it also use for Christmas/New Year countdowns, or other related topic to emphasize data gathering and issue explanation.\n\n==Weekend edition==\nOn February 21, 2010, the weekend edition of the show was launched, replacing ''[[GMA Weekend Report]]'', and originally anchored by [[Pia Arcangel]] and [[Jiggy Manicad]].<ref>{{cite news|title=24 Oras Weekend premieres this Sunday, February 21|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/5612/24-oras-weekend-premieres-this-sunday-february-21|accessdate=April 26, 2018|work=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=February 20, 2012}}</ref> On April 21, 2018, Manicad left the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/04/22/1808377/jiggy-manicad-leaves-media-next-level-public-service|title=Jiggy Manicad leaves media for \u2018next level\u2019 of public service {{!}} Philstar.com|website=philstar.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/pepalerts/cabinet-files/21675/jiggy-manicad-magpapaalamna-sa-mga-programa-niya-sa-gma-news|title=Jiggy Manicad, nagpaalam na sa mga programa niya sa GMA News|last=PEP.ph|date=2018-04-20|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2018/04/watch-jiggy-manicad-announces-his-departure-from-the-media-industry.html|title=Watch: Jiggy Manicad announces his departure from the media industry|website=www.medianewser.com|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref><ref>http://www.medianewser.com/2018/10/jiggy-manicad-makes-senatorial-bid-official.html?m=1</ref> In August 2018, [[Ivan Mayrina]] became co-anchor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/43076/ivan-mayrina-co-anchors-24-oras-weekend/story|title=Ivan Mayrina co-anchors '24 Oras Weekend'|website=www.gmanetwork.com|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2018/08/ivan-mayrina-officially-the-new-co-anchor-of-24-oras-weekend.html?m=1|title=Ivan Mayrina officially the new co-anchor of '24 Oras Weekend'|website=www.medianewser.com|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref>\n\n==Regional newscasts==\nOn January 29, 2016, GMA Regional TV announced the return of ''Balitang Amianan'' and ''Balitang Bisdak'' on February 1, 2016 as a pre-programming and later preemption of the first 30 minutes of [[Wowowin]], after more than a year of using 24 Oras brand. As a result, ''24 Oras Southern Mindanao'' remained to its branding since November 10, 2014 (rebranded to ''24 Oras Davao'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/GMARegionalTV/posts/1014497441949224|title=GMA Regional TV|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, 2017, the Davao edition adopted the graphics, OBB, and soundtrack of the national edition; while the two other regional newscasts changed only the graphics and OBB similarly to the said national newscast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m_-RL1Crg0o|title=24 Oras Davao OBB (January 2, 2017-present)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZIpUI6SdPNA|title=Balitang Amianan OBB (January 2, 2017-present)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nOn August 25, 2017, ''24 Oras Davao'' ended its more than 2-year run to pave way for [[Mindanao]]-wide newscast, [[One Mindanao]].\n\n===Previous regional versions===\n*''[[24 Oras Ilokano]]'' (GMA Ilocos) <small>(replaced by [[Balitang Amianan]])</small>\n*''24 Oras North Central Luzon/24 Oras Amianan'' (GMA Dagupan) <small>(reverted to [[Balitang Amianan]])</small>\n*''[[24 Oras Bikol]]'' (GMA Bicol) \n*''24 Oras Western Visayas/[[Ratsada 24 Oras]]'' (GMA Iloilo) <small>(replaced by [[One Western Visayas]])</small>\n*''24 Oras Central Visayas'' (GMA Cebu) <small>(reverted to [[Balitang Bisdak]])</small>\n*''[[24 Oras Northern Mindanao]]'' (GMA Northern Mindanao) <small>(replaced by [[One Mindanao]])</small>\n*''24 Oras Southern Mindanao''/''24 Oras Davao'' (GMA Davao) <small>(replaced by [[One Mindanao]])</small>\n\n==Anchors==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Mike Enriquez in White Plains, Quezon City.jpg\n|caption1 = Mike Enriquez serves as an anchor.\n|width1 = 150\n}}\n\n* [[Mel Tiangco]] {{small|(since 2004)}}\n* [[Mike Enriquez]] {{small|(since 2004)}}\n* [[Vicky Morales]] {{small|(since 2014)}}\n\n;Weekend anchors\n* [[Pia Arcangel]] {{small|(since 2010; interim anchor for Tiangco and Soho)}}\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]] {{small|(since 2018)}}\n\n;Segment anchors\n* Nathaniel \"Mang Tani\" Cruz {{small|(since 2012; ''IM Ready: GMA Weather'' anchor)}}\n* [[Iya Villania]] {{small|(since 2015; for ''Chika Minute'' segment)}}\n* Nelson Canlas {{small|(since 2013; ''Chika Minute'' weekend anchor)}}\n\n;Former anchors\n* [[Atom Araullo]] {{small|(2004\u20132005; ''Atomic Sports'' anchor, 2018; interim anchor)}}\n* [[Pia Guanio]] {{small|(2004\u20132015; ''Chika Minute'' weekday anchor)}}